Tactics pools might work for two groups of veteran commandoes. However
in most traveller games I am dealing with there is a  mixed group
of scouts, merchants , and some muscle. They do not have a decided
way of fighting together.

Lack of trust is not the issue. The issue is that on a roleplaying
level these individuals should not know how to fight together as a
unit until they have been together. Individuals may see another
approach than what is occurring.


> > refereeing and playing various rpgs for almost 20 years, I\'ve found
> > that conflicts among player characters that lead to a lack of trust
> > on the battlefield are the most likely causes of failed missions and
> > failed games.  I suspect the same is true for real world small groups
> > engaged in organized violence.
>
>
> I\'ve found that mature players generally have no problems acting as a
group.
> Sure there are disagreements, but they get resolved at the planning stages.
> When I started reffing games for my high school students I had a hard time
> adjusting to the "every player for himself" style of the less mature
players.

What about in cases of surprise?

What about in situations where the unforseen or unpredicted occur?

Matthew Harelick


