    'body' => 'According to the designers, the reason for making Tactics a roving modifier
for combat was that otherwise it was practically useless once the battle
started.  Having the modifier means that even if the player has no tactical
sense, the character still gets an advantage.

The justification is that a well-coordinated group of individuals is more
than the sum of its parts.

Some house rules I used:

The maximum number of Tactics Pool points that can be \'spent\' at a time is
the level of Leadership skill possessed by the groups leader.  (This reflects
the advantages of Leadership for player characters, who practically never
fail morale checks and run away).  

The group must be in communication for the points to be shared.

A player can withhold their Tactics points, but then they get no benefit from
belonging to the group (no warnings or communication allowed).  Deciding that
each player can use their points themselves is something else.  In the event
of arguments, the group\'s leader decides (but the players may mutiny...).

