  I remember reading about the initial jumps, I just don\'t remember 
where.  There is an article by Marc W. Miller in JTAS #24 on Jumpspace. 
Here is what it says about microjumps.

    "Any jump of less than one parsec is considered to be a microjump.  
Sometimes, it can be advantageous to jump within a system rather than 
use maneuver drives.  If normal acceleration and deceleraton would take 
more than a week, a microjump is more efficient.  At 1G, any distance 
greater than one billion km would be more efficient using a microjump.
    Microjumps can also confuse an observer or enemy.  Because a ship\'s 
destination cannot be predicted, a microjump within a system still 
leaves an impression that the ship has left; a week later, it emerges 
from jump in the same system, to the observer\'s confusion."

    I know that there is another mention of microjumps, I just can\'t 
remember where.  Anyway I hope this little bit helps.

                        Zane
