    'topic' => ' Microjumps',
    'body' => 'In xboat 338, Ethan Henry <ehenry@magmacom.com> asked about microjumps:
>> Note that in Classic Traveller, microjumps are part of the established
>> background history...

>OK, not that I doubt you, but where is this written?

I believe that microjumps were first proposed in "From Port to Jump-point",
(I think by Leroy Guatney), in JTAS #23(??). He pointed out that travel
from Regina\'s main star to its binary companion is done by microjump,
because 1 week in jumpspace is quicker than travel through normal space.

>2) it would be tricky to jump insystem due to all those damn gravity
>   wells moving around all over the place.

The original article had a suggested "house rule" that the better the
jump drive, the smaller the gravity well target could be. That is, a
jump-1 ship would aim for the largest gravity well in a system (the
main star). A jump-2 ship could target the next biggest well (eg.
Jupiter in the Sol system). A jump-6 ship could target Earth itself
(being a much smaller target). Note that Naval ships - traditionally
with better j-drives - could hit your mainworld with no problems.
(Leroy, can you add anything to this outline??)

Matthew Harelick commented that:

>Tactics pools might work for two groups of veteran commandoes. However
>...a  mixed group...do not have a decided way of fighting together.

The use of a tactics pool was discussed by DGP; they had the "old
veteran sergeant" instructing a newbie on how to point his gun,
"squeeze the trigger, don\'t pull it", etc. This was the justification
for pooling the skill.

However, they ALWAYS said that the rules were a guideline, and not to
be hampered by them. Some suggestions I can make are:
1. Make the total Tactics pool only equal to their highest individual
   Leader skill (a DGP suggestion).
2. Tell your players that they cannot drw on their Tactics until they
   train together, or somehow (up to you) gain more "experience" of
   working as a group. Gradually increase their Tactics pool as they
   improve. Note that this is also a way to get a bunch of players
   to CO-OPERATE together (very Sesame St).

- Hyphen
  (David Jaques-Watson)


