    'body' => '>For an idea about other elements than carbon as building
>blocks for life, take a look at a periodic table and pick
>common elements with the same valens (sp?) as carbon.
>I believe sulphur is a viable alternative too.

No, neither Chlorine or Sulphur is a likely candidate (nor do they have the
same 
Valence as Carbon) - you are probably mis-remembering Silicon.

As for resistance to HCl, you don\'t need slime-covering - only earth type, 
non-acid resistant life needs that. If it originated in an ocean of HCl, it
will 
have a native chemistry which *uses* and takes advantage of acids, rather
than 
being vulnerable to them.  In terms of stable chemistry in an acid
environment, 
Silicon is rather unlikely (for all the inertness of Solicone rubber) -- the 
long chain molecules needed for bio-chemistry have weaker bonds if they are 
Si-Si rather than C-C.  I\'d make them carbon-based, but not on Earth style 
proteins, DNA etc; and I\'d give most of them an acid-secretion touch,
assuming 
they take advantage of their chemistry to corrode rocks (if plants) or to 
concentrate acid within themselves as an attack form if animals. (Yes, even
if 
more resistant than we are, they\'d still be vulnerable to concetrated acids -

this *isn\'t* DnD!)
For breathing, they\'d probably use a Cl - HCl cycle, so I\'d expect some free
Cl 
gas, which is pronouncedly green.
There may well be oxygen involved too; an alternative to Cl - HCl would be
HCl - 
HOCl (Hypochlorous acid, a bleaching/oxidising agent) - that also leads to
the 
likelihood of Chlorates and perChlorates as common substances, and they are 
potent oxidisers (sugar + weedkiller -> Bang!)

Acids are also *very* corrosive to rocks, so the landscape will be much more 
eroded than Earth: rounded, with few sharp ridges or peaks and with many
rocks 
pock-maked or cut into bizzare forms along lines of weakness (like the Mesas
in 
some deserts).  There will be no limestone at all on a world with this much 
acid-rain!
