    'body' => 'Deepspace Rendezvous, that is jumping into a parsec area without a star and
meeting another vessel, is easy enough if you are fairly patient.  I 
presume that the two vessels are jumping from two different systems.  (If 
they are jumping from the same system, similar jump parameters will have 
them arrive in about the same place; they will easily find each other.)

>From two different systems, the jump exit points have little to 
accurately coordinate from.  "Accurate" in this case means within 10 
million kilometers (MKm).  This does not say that they cannot come out 
that close together; just that it is unpredictable.

Selecting a rendezvous point based on "intersection of line Star A to 
Star B with line Star C to Star D" should work just fine, probably 
putting the vessels well within 1 Mkm of each other - enough that radio 
beacons or flashing light patterns can be easily detected.

Actually, radio beacons, regularly flashing lights, and similar methods 
should work just fine out to 10-100 Mkm. However, it is not particularly 
stealthy - are you expecting someone else in the area at the time?

What I meant by patient is that you may come out a few 100 Mkm from your 
rendezvous point, which may take some time to cover.  Or you could come 
out within 2km of your friend.  Since the local parameters are difficult 
to pin down that tightly due to a lack of referents, the variance is 
somewhat wider than jumping into a populated system. (This last sentence 
is more based on my belief of how the mechanics of jump-drive should 
operate; if you feel differently, your performance will differ).

					Ted7

