    'date' => 'Tue, 1 Aug 1995 15:10:34  0500',
    'body' => 'David Elrick <Dave.Elrick@ps.co.uk> wrote:

>Astrography: The science of mapping interstellar space.
[...]
>placed at one parsec intervals. By convention, the concentric ring passing 
>through Reference/Capital is labelled the 10,000th ring, and is used as a 
>baseline. Similarly, the ray of latitude extending from the centre of the 
>galaxy through Reference/Capital is designated as the first ray. 

..and Reference/Core is in hex 0140, which puts it in the lower left-hand
corner of Core sector.  This suggests that the sector boundaries may be
defined by ring/rays, with the rimward border of Core sector following
10000 ring and the spinward border following ray 1.  Then the trailing
border would be ray 33 and the border to galactic coreward, the 9960 ring.

Of course, if sector borders strictly follow rings and rays, they aren\'t
*quite* straight anymore, and they pick up some problems with minor but
obvious distortion from the traditional grid the farther they get from 
the Imperial Core.  It could be that the sector grid is based on the IISS
navigational system, but doesn\'t follow it slavishly.  However, it does
explain why regions are "sectors"; they can be thought of as being roughly
sectors of the galactic disk. 

This notation may explain the what the "Prime Radiant" mentioned in 
_Survival Margin_ is; it could be a fancy name for ray 1.  

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu> 

