    'topic' => 'RE: self-destructing fusion plants',
    'body' => 'consider two sorts of plausible fusion power:

	hot fusion (like JET and other experimnts in C20 earth)

	cold fusion (hey, this is SF, so maybe it works!)

for a decent explosion you need a rapid discharge of *lots* of energy, typically 
the equivalent of runnign a power plant for a prolonged period but discharged
over a very short period -- anything else produces a messy melt down and 
possible fires, but doesn\'t go Bang!!...
 
Cold fusion isn\'t going to blow up worse than TNT at most; In cold fusion we\'re 
supposed to see the catalytic fusion of limited quantities of hydrogen which has 
been absorbed into a spongy metal catalyst under pressure in the presence of a 
high electric current -- the output is much higher than burning the hydrogen gas 
in oxygen. If it fails, the fusion stops, and the gas may be released from the 
metal catalyst...
The stored energy for instant release is only that bound up in compressing the 
hydrogen, and in burning the hydrogen on contact with air.  I think you\'d be 
safer with this than if an equivalent pertol engine blew up (as the petrol 
engine holds more inflammable fuel per power delivered!)


Hot fusion is what most people think of, but it still isn\'t going to produce a 
large bang.  The reactor is a large bulky vessel most of which generates 
magnetic fields (or SF "force fields") to hold  a hot low density ionized plasma 
- specifically, to hold it away from the reactor\'s metal walls where it would

(a) cut into the metal, (b) cool and (c) be contaminated so it stopped fusing..

If the plasma expands and/or mixes with cold matter, it rapidly falls below the 
neccessary conditions for fusion.  Hydrogen/deuterium/tritium/helium fusion 
reactions in plasmas are all susceptible to poisoning by heavy elements like 
iron from metal walls, which saps the plasma. 

As far as most kiddies-on-grav-bikes problems go, the biggest problem is the 
megawatt heat exhaust the standard models seem to pump out, presumably torching 
anything nearby as they pass by!

You could consider the catastrophic collapse of a *large* reactor as being 
equivalent to the blast of a Fusion Gun of some suitable size, but even in this 
case, you aren\'t going to get a significant discharge before it flickers out as 
the plasma expands/cools (fusion guns are specially designed to sustain the 
reaction and cause damage - reactors are designed to produce steady power (and 
be safe in normal operations)).  If I remember right, a lot of the discharge 
energy in a fusion beam is not in the fusion occurring during the beam 
discharge, but in a confined fusion burn which heats a sealed quantity of plasma 
before release - a souped up verion of the plasma gun. 
Such a fusion blast could be quite big, but not like the Trekkie blasts...

The reactors with the greatest liability are those playing with bulk quantities 
of Anti-Matter -- which is of course. just what Star Trek has!  If the 
containment of a large quantity of hot anti-matter fails, so that a mass 
annihilation occurs with the surrounding normal matter (reactor walls), then you 
could be in for a nasty bang.
If designing such a system for safety, a starship engineer should arrange that 
in the worst case of failure, the A-M gas vents into space, *away* from any bits 
of spaceship and other matter it can react with!
	(I\'d also ban such a thing from entering the atmosphere of any planet I 
	controlled, lest it vent and blast into the air!)

If you wanted a self destructor, chuck in a large mix of matter-anti-matter and 
confine it for as long as possible, then as the containment fields begin to 
fail, switch them off.....

The easiest way to self-destruct a Trav ship is to let off your own Nukes if 
any, or if a warship, to play with the Nuclear Dampers turning them into full

reverse on said Nukes.
