    'topic' => '3D Near Space Viewer',
    'body' => 'Greeting All!
    I have been working for some time with another fellow
on a program to view and explore nearby stars in 3D space.
It comes with a database of the nearest 2000 odd stars.
    Although originally inspired by the works of C.J.Cherryh
it contains real data and is likely to be of use to any
hard-science RPGers as well. Traveller 2300 people should
love it.
    It can be found on ftp.maths.tcd.ie somewhere in the
pub/jaymin/ch directory structure (I\'m not sure exactly where).
Appended to this is the begining of the documentation.
    It would be interesting to see it used as the basis for
a 3D TCS game...
                      Jo


                             ABOUT CHVIEW

For as long our species has gazed into the night sky, we have been awed by
the vision of countless stars.  Having now deduced that stars are radiant
suns like our own, many cannot help but imagine what we might find if we
traveled to those faraway, unknown places.  With no means of interstellar
travel today, we can only dream that our descendants will.

[This Beta-test, WINDOWS-based version of] CHVIEW is intended as a three-
dimensional aid to:  viewing some of the nearer stars of our galaxy;
navigating the distances and gravity "gradients" between them;  accessing
basic information (and updating what we know); and, hopefully, having some
fun.  The current data file provides about 2,600 known stars within 100
light-years of Earth.  Future plans include modules for selecting a star
(or multiple star system) and, based on available data and known
astronomical relationships, for creating your own star system (of planets,
moons, asteroids, Kuiper belt, Oort cloud/cometary halo, and even human
colonies or space communities), for voyaging in faster-than-light (FTL)
"starships", and the like.

CHVIEW is brought to you by Jo Grant and Ben Lin with the assistance of
other subscribers of the CHERRYHLIST discussion group at
JAYMIN@MATHS.TCD.IE.  While some of us have been collecting star data for
years, all of us are fans of the Hugo-winning author, C.J. Cherryh, who has
developed an intriguing scenario for human colonization of our neighboring
stars.  As you may guessed, the name "CHVIEW" is a tribute to her.
Depending on where you obtained this copy of CHVIEW, in fact, some of the
"Place Names" assigned to selected stars may be the names of Cherryh\'s
fictional human colonies -- easily changed to suit your fancy.

CHVIEW (program, data, and documentation files) is provided for personal
use only.  Written permission must be obtained for all other uses.  All
rights are retained for CHVIEW(c).  Comments and suggestions are welcome:
Jo_Grant.lotusint@crd.lotus.com and BLin@mailstorm.dot.gov.
