    'topic' => ' ahhh...here we go!!! (on computer programming)',
    'body' => 'As Max states you may want to skip this message, if you are not interested
in the running of computers, although I\'m trying to put them in a Traveller
prospective.

----

Mega Trav and TNE state that you have to place three computers on your ship,
for backup, if one gets killed you go to the next, this is a poor view of
computers used for flying at the mo. I\'ve always played that the three
main computers are doing a fault tolarence job, all running at the same time
and comparing results, the majority vote wins, and gets implemented. Just
like systems today. The reasons there is fault tolerance today, is because
computers are inherently unreliable, and software is inherently unreliable.
If you trusted just one computer a bit error could mean death, or lots of
money lost in companies. Two fault tolerance systems (each with three or more
machines) running different software which produce the same result. The point
I was making is that even fault tolerance systems aren\'t completly reliable,
although in Trav times this will be improved a lot, but how reliable do you
have to be when doing a jump .... when bit errors, or imperfect fuel cause
misjumps at best, and death at worst, that\'s even if you return to normal
space.

> " a *= b->c(); " or "blast that fu..g Vargr "

a*=b->c() is clearly defined, as it is derived from maths, and the language
you are programming in, while Language (spocken ie English) is not. Dose the
above statement mean :- kill the Vargr, play load music at the Vargr, kill
the Vargr who is engaging in the act of, as opposed to the Vargr standing
next to him who is not .... Is the person just swearing at the Vargar, or is
the statment a command for the computer to exicute the Vargr, etc etc etc etc

... this is a massive qulitative difference to a computer, there is not a
computer at the moment which can make this distinktion. In Traveller times
they will be better at it, having had three thousand year of practice, but
will probably still not be perfect ....

There is no absolute definition of AI, and probably never will be. What I am
studying is not Intellegence that is Artificial. I am not studdying machines
or computers built by us that are capable of free thought or action. AI at
the mo is Knowledged based systems, connectionisum, vision, etc etc. But
this is not "Artificial Intellegence" this is AI. To but this in Traveller
terms the Virus, or the chips on Cyberline (?) are not AI they are
Natural Intellegence. To say they are AI would be like saying the Vargr are
K9 Intellegent. The life form that was found, was naturally occuring in it\'s
own enviroment, it just happened to look and behave like a human built
computer, so GDW call it AI (not that it wasn\'t helped by pure silicon). If
people think that the original chip were not capable of intelegence without
outside help (ie pure silicon) try feeding one lab rat proteen, and another
no proteen, and see which reaches the potentioal of the rat spechies (just a
rough analogy).

Right back to compilers .... if someone rights the compiler in machine code,
that person is at least as good, and most probably better at writing machine
code than the compiler stop. Software can never be better than the people
who write it, because they write it. If the best compiler writer in the
world wrote a compiler, he could still improve it .... therefore it could
not be as good as the writer .... therefore then computer is not as good
as the person at writing machine code .... stop. I`m not saying I\'m better,
but the person who wrote the compiler is. This would also apply in
Traveller, the computer is only as good as it\'s software, and someone has to
write that software, so the software is not as good as the person who wrote
it, because the software can be improved.

Thanks

Ewan


