    'index' => 'ab664',
    'body' => 'This may have come up before, but I don\'t remember it: 
If, in normal space, starship A is carrying starship B
internally and starship B jumps, what happens?  What if 
they\'re in jump space?

I think that the answer (to the first question) depends on
A\'s mass:  If A is massy enough to exert significant
gravity, B is in danger of a misjump.  I think that A
would have be very large.  This leads to another question:
 How large is the largest body whose gravity can be
ignored in determining safe jump points? Luna-sized? Big
asteroid? Small asteroid? Just right asteroid?

I think that the answer to the second question is
substantial destruction of starship A and misjump of
starship B.  A\'s jump grid is keeping the effects of jump
space\'s physics away from the interior of A.  B\'s jump
drive tears a whole in normal space in the interior of A. 
This intrusion of jump space into A causes the damage
described in the canon.  B misjumps because it can\'t write 
a jump program based on a normal space location.

As usual, I solicit your comments.

Thank you for your comments on self-destruct mechanisms --
reflecting on them has changed my mind about them, not
least because by the time a ship is subject to boarding,
it\'s so shot up that it probably doesn\'t matter if the
enemy gets it. 

--Glenn
