The jump-in-jump statement stems from an article in an
OLD issue of Challenge, where Marc Miller eleborates on
the principles of jump space. In this article, he gives an
overview of (Imperial) research to break the 6-parsec
barrier. This includes forcing and trying to control a
misjump and jumping from the insides of a ship in jump
space. The article states quite qlearly (as far as I
remember) that the jump-in-jump procedure is impossible.
Thus, according to canon, jumping from a ship in jump
space is not possible. As someone mentioned, I think
DGP eleborated on the topic (or a similar one) in SOM.

(The forcing of misjumps, BTW, has up until "now"
resulted in navigators being able to determine the direction
to travel but not the distance, or the distance but not the
direction.)

The ideas about jump-1 only being able to enter the largest
gravity well in the system, jump-2 also the next largest, etc.
is not canon. Do I remember correctly if I say that these
ideas where spawned by the discussion of the profitability
of Vargr corsairs?

Some of the topics mentioned here I have less than perfect
recall about, so please forgive (but correct) any mistakes.

Mark Seemann
ms@oem.dk
