first, the 100 diameter rule doesn\'t produce a constant g-field, even if
you consider bodies of equal desnity:

   planet mass          M = k R^3

   grav force on ship   g = G M / D^2 
                          = K R^3 / D^2

   so at jump dist, D = n R (n=10 or 100,...)

                        g = K R^3 / (n R)^2 
                          = K R / n^2

   which scales linearly, increasing as the world/sun size increases (K
differs for earth world, gas giant and suns but the scaling law is the
same...)

A grav intensity measure also ignores the g-force of the Galaxy as a
whole... we are all orbiting the centre of the Galaxy, remember!

What does have a constant, non-scaling value is the <rate of change of g
with distance>, the "flatness" of the g-field

   rate of change       dg/dD = -2 K R^3 / D^3     (differentiating...)

   at D=nR              dg/dD = -2 K R^3 / (nR)^3
                              = -2 K / n^3

the new formula shows that at the 10 radius and 100 radius jump distances,
the flatness of the g-field depends slightly on density (the K factor) and
hugely on the distance multiple 
The change in field gradient from 10 diams to 100 diams is 1000-fold!
The corrolary to that is that a doubling of density only shifts the 100 diams
to
126 diams
