11/8-95 Jerry Alexandratos wrote:

>Trying to be parsimonious, jump is entering jumpspace
>and coming out at some other point a week later.  The
>only restrictions should be that you should be 100
>diameters out to jump safely, and you should be 100
>diameters out just to be on the safe side when you arrive.
>Misjumps may (and will in some instances) occur if you
>don\'t meet some of the safety criteria.

Actually, according to the SOM, a body emerging from
jump space will *automatically* emerge at least 100
diameters from any mass. That means that you can\'t do a
dangerous jump *to* a point inside the 100 diameter sphere
of an object. You can, however, make dangerous jumps
by jumping *from* such a point.

And Mark F. Cook wrote:

[Description of artificial gravity closely resembling the one
given by DGP snipped]

>As a result, two starships could be parked within 100
>meters (or less) of one another and either ship could jump
>successfully without being influenced by the gravitics of
>the other ship.  As for one ship jumping from *inside* the
>hold of another ship, I maintain that the result would be
>fundementally the same as if the smaller ship tried to jump
>from a starport launch-pit, while still planetside:
>disasterous.

Maybe according to SOM (I don\'t quite remember where I
read this, but I\'m pretty sure it\'s canon), you\'ll still have to
be outside 100 diameters of another starship to jump
safely. A starship also has mass (artificial gravity or no
artificial gravity) - they are even pretty dense.

Wasn\'t this question aswered in a Q&A in either TD or
MTJ? (one of the later I think)

And 11/8-95 Chris wrote:

>     Can anyone postulate how such a thing as jump
>packets might be possible or why it would be
>?impossible??

How would you get a jump field bubble to close around
a non-physical thing? By TL 15, it can\'t be done.
Remember that instant matter transportation is not
impossible in Traveller, it\'s just first possible at *very* high
tech levels. In fact, the ability to construct matter trans
portals is a weighty factor of defining these high tech levels.

In the article by Marc Miller I mentioned in an earlier
message, he says that once TL 15 and jump-6 is reached
no further development of jump drive is possible, because
jump drive is sort of a very well-working mistake. The
principles of jump space does not allow jumps to be made
more than six parsecs in a week. They do allow for
instantaneous transport of matter from one end of the
galaxy to the other, though. Alas, the ability to do that first
occurs at TL 23 or something like that.

Mark Seemann
