    'from' => 'PEDRO PTREVOR@delphi.com',
    'topic' => 'Jump limits (safe distance minimums)',
    'body' => '
Recently some people have revisited the old idea of redefining
the \'100 diameter\' jump limit in turms of gravity.  I wrote  a
variant on this posted in  Xboat  169, 171,  and  174.  I  can
repost it if necessary.  The jist of it  was  about  computing
the gravitational \'stress\' at differing ranges and using  that
to determine jump difficulty.

Stress was measured in pS (\'pico es\') where 1 pS =  2.93995e-5
gees ...

    Stress Factor      Difficulty     Comment
    ----   ----   ----
         < 1pS         Routine        The \'100 diameter\' limit
       1pS -     3pS   Routine +1
       3pS -    10pS   Routine +2
      10pS -    32pS   Routine +3
      32pS -   100pS   Difficult      The \'10 diameter\' limit
     100pS -   316pS   Difficult +1
     316pS -  1000pS   Difficult +2
    1000pS -  3162pS   Difficult +3
    3162pS - 10000pS   Formidable     Real close!

Using L (in miles) = 4000 * (M/G)^0.5 the 1pS boundary for the
following worlds (assuming standard density) ...

    World   1pS boundary
    Size    (in diameters)
    ----   ----
      R            ?
      S            5
      0            4
      1           33
      2           46
      3           56
      4           65
      5           73
      6           80
      7           86
      8           92
      9           98
      A          103
    SGG/60       113
    LGG/170      190
    Star/875     487

Note for our Sun the 1pS boundary is at 492.148 solar diameters
= 4.5775 AU.

As I said I can repost the full article with rationale and techno
bable included, if wanted.

Regards PLST

