    'topic' => 'Antigravity, Jump & Computers',
    'body' => 'I=92ve been following the recent debates of Jumps and Computers, so=20
here=92s my 2credits worth.
----
I=92m a CT player.  I=92ve not even made the change to MT.  So all my=20
comments are based on my view of the CT world.
----
Internal Grav fields
The internal grav fields generated to keep the crews feet on the=20
floor, do not have the usual inverse-squared law that mass induced=20
gravitation has.  The field drops off very quickly outside the=20
influence of the grav plates.  The =93well=94 is square, rather that the=20
bell shaped one planets cause.  This means that the field has no=20
noticeable effect outside the hull  of the spaceship.  OR even if you=20
are standing on the hull!

Jumps
The 10 and 100 diameter limits (as well as been easy to play, from=20
the UPP) are a problem of gravitational energy.  The jump field moves=20
a given volume into jumpspace, and it reemerges at a distant point. =20
The distance you wish to travel depends on how much energy you burn. =20
(Marc Miller=92s article in an old JoTAS).  As there is this energy=20
dependence, any distortion of space-time is going to be a problem.=20
This is just a gravitatioonal well problem, it is not affected by=20
kienetic energy of accelleration.  As I understand general reletivity=20
neither of these cause distortions like a gravitational well.

Jumping from within another ship is just impossible.  Calculating the=20
jump from real-space to real-space is complex enougth.  Even if you=20
could calculate the jump, it would want to return to the universe of=20
the jump bubble that had been jumped from.  As this bubble would no=20
longer exist, there would be nowhere for the ship to return to,=20
effectivly destroying it!

Computers
I agree the computer sizes seem excessive but consided what it has to=20
do.
The shipboard computer must contain enougth redundant systems for=20
safe operation.  It will need at its core something like a cray or=20
connection machine for jump calculations.  I assume they are like=20
fluid-flow work, there=92s no analytical solution, you have to go=20
through many thousand interations to get the solution.
If you include extra engineering and environmental controls, and all=20
the sensor operations, the size of the computers doesn=92t seem to bad.

The two gripes I do have (and I=92m trying to fix) are.
1. The programme space - most computers don=92t have enougth space to=20
run a useful set of programmes even for routine operations, let alone=20
survey or combat.
2. No improvement - The hand computer (TL13) is described as having=20
the perfomance of the model I shipboard computer!  Yet there is no=20
improvement of computer models at high tech levels!


----
