    'index' => 'ab714',
    'topic' => 'Computers in CT',
    'body' => 'Alun Moon:

> The two gripes I do have (and I\'m trying to fix) are.
> 1. The programme space - most computers don\'t have enougth space to
> run a useful set of programmes even for routine operations, let alone
> survey or combat.
> 2. No improvement - The hand computer (TL13) is described as having
> the perfomance of the model I shipboard computer!  Yet there is no
> improvement of computer models at high tech levels!

You might try +1 program per tech level above minimum. This represents 
increased ability to multitask. Alternatively, allow computer sizes given 
in Book 2 to be "size at TL of introduction". If built at a higher TL, 
then the size is reduced (building TL - introduction TL) models.

Hence a Model/7 computer built at TL15 would be the size of a Model/5 
computer at its introductory TL (11).

Minimum computer size is 1 ton (Model 1). After minimum size is reached, 
allow +1 program running per TL of improvement. [Note these are for 
shipboard computers, which have a lot of dedicated electronics linked 
straight to the weapons systems, avionics, jump drive...]

Cost will be +1 model number for each TL of miniaturisation, so the TL15 
Model/7 will cost the same as a Model/9. [+20% per TL equivalent over 15...]
It\'s still cheaper to produce less efficient systems.

Thus, we might decide our model/7 should be made slightly smaller 
(model/6), cost the same as a model/8, and have +1 program capacity.
One would call this a model/7+1; an unmodified model/7 at TL15 would be a 
model/7+2.

Other scheme: +model number/2 per TL above introduction (round down) on 
program space (both active and stored). This may keep the advantage of 
higher model numbers better.

High Guard warships (except fighters) all tend to have maximum computers 
(unless they\'re FASA\'s, in which case *boom*) and will be unaffected in 
price and performance by this scheme. Merchants will also have the same 
computers (because miniaturised ones are more expensive) but these will 
have higher capacity. Under the +model/2 scheme, *all* starship computers 
(at least model/1, TL 5 or 6. I forget which) become model/1+2 or 1+1 
(depending on whether it\'s TL5 or TL6 for model/1).

A model 1+2 is twice as capable as a model/1 (CPU 4 versus CPU 2).

Perhaps if performance for a computer betters that of a higher model, it 
could be reclassified (at no extra cost). Thus, the model/1+2 (with CPU 4 
and storage 6) can be reclassified as a model/2 (with CPU 3 and storage 6).
This means smaller computers can be used for higher model numbers at no 
extra cost in miniaturisation. This is advantageous for larger merchant 
starships, which need a minimum computer size to jump -- that computer 
comes cheaper at higher TLs. The advantages for military craft 
(especially light fighters) are obvious.

I\'d recommend using the currency conversion rates into Imperial credits 
based on TL and starport (with an Imperial being TL15, starport A) if 
this scheme is used -- so higher tech is *always* a little more 
expensive, but generally better -- enough so to outweigh the extra cost.

[All CT figures quoted from memory as examples only.]

How\'s that sound, for ideas?


Nick Munn
University Chemical Laboratory, Lensfield Road, Cambridge, CB2 1EW, England

