I have always used the following approach to whether or not a sapient is a
citizen of the Imperium: Have they been employed within Imperial space for
4 years or more, paying Imperial taxes, and requested an Imperial Passport.

If a being meets those requirements, is not currently wanted for violations
of Imperial Law, and has no history of treasonous behavior, it\'s pretty
much automatic, although I require that they wait 6-9 months while the Navy
searches it\'s files.

As for Civil Rights of Imperial Citizens, I have always used the following:
Freedom of Interstellar Movement, Freedom from weapons of mass destruction
(See also the Rules of War), the right to send written appeal to one\'s
Noble representative, and the right to live.

The Library data only defines one crime clearly, that being Murder. Hence
the right to life.

Note that I did not mention freedom to leave a world; The Traveller
Adventure has several items about exit visas from worlds. Individual worlds
may restrict access to space, but once past orbit, space belongs to the
Imperium.

According to my players, there should also be one other express civil
right: the right to a minimum standard of safety aboard spacecraft, which
includes standardized Transponder, Safety, and Design standards.

Also note that the Imperium is NOT TRULY a government of law, but of
tradition. It is tradition that provides the basis of these rights, not
written laws (Edicts).


-Wil

