    'body' => 'Right, I left taxes out of my post on Citizenship Issues in the 
Imperium.  The right to pay taxes is important.  In my Imperium, taxation 
works more or less as follows:

Individuals are not subject to any direct Imperial taxation (but they are 
subject to the Imperial draft, which is another story).  Imperial member 
states that are not directly controlled by nobles are subject to a tax 
based on their gross state product.  The tax may be paid in cash or 
kind.  The subsector duke is usually the first tax collector, and usually 
gets to spend the money subject to approval by the sector duke, who in 
turn must get approval from the archduke.  These approvals are generally 
vague and broad.  The subsector duke may submit a 5-year plan, which, 
after discussion and modification, will be accepted by the sector duke 
and submitted to the archduke as part of a 10-year plan for the sector, 
and on up the line.  The plans may be many years out of date.

Individuals are subject to taxation by member states, based on local 
law, and may be subject to more than one such tax.  For example, a 
citizen of Regina residing on and working in Rhylanor who sends money 
home every month will be subject to Rhylanor\'s noncitizen/resident income 
tax, Regina\'s citizen/nonresident income tax, and the various sales and 
property taxes attaching to whatever transactions she enters into.

Non-LIC business organizations are taxed basically like individuals -- 
i.e., only under local law.  The taxation of business organizations 
(which includes non-profits, educational institutions, churches, etc., as 
well as regular for-profit businesses) is complex, detailed, and often in 
conflict from one member state to another.  Non-LIC businesses that grow 
large enough to attract the attention of the Ministry of Taxation are 
generally awarded LIC status.

LIC business organizations are (1) substantially involved in interstellar 
commerce; (2) very large (there is probably a BCr or TCr number, but I 
don\'t know what it is); (3) publicly held (at least partly).  LIC 
corporations must report annually to the Imperial government.  At least 
three Ministries receive reports:  the Ministry of Taxation (of course); 
the Ministry of Finance (which oversees disclosure under the Imperial 
securities laws, which only apply to the publicly traded securities of 
LIC businesses); and whatever Ministry or Ministries govern the primary 
businesses of the company.  For example, Tukera Lines, LIC, reports to 
the Ministry of Transportation as well as Taxation and Finance.

Of course, non-LIC interstellar operations, like Jameson Factors and 
Uakye Trading Partners, make certain payments to the Imperium that are in 
effect taxes.  For example, their ships pay berthing fees to the Ministry 
of Transportation.  Interstellar ships are subject to the engineering and 
safety standards of the Ministry of Transportion (they were formerly 
subject to standards set by the Ministry of Standards, but the turf war 
between MoT and MoS resulting in a MoT win, but that\'s another story); 
they may be subject to fine for continuing violations.

--Glenn Goffin
(also sometimes posting as ggoffin@igc.apc.org)

