    'index' => 'ab745',
    'body' => '
> From: Alvin Plummer <alvin.plummer@sheridanc.on.ca>

> "Any sentient lifeform within Imperial borders, regardless of its origin, 
> is a protected being, and thus a citizen of the Third Imperium."
>                                    - Cleon, 17

> Yipes!  


> Actually, I think that it\'s actually a workable concept,
> but I have no idea how to do it.  What about those who
> have no alliegence to the Imperium, but just happen to be
> within it\'s borders?  Is there any such thing as dual
> citizenship?

I\'ve always assumed that multiple citizenship was part of
Imperial life, and that almost everyone was a citizen of
both a world* and the Imperium, bearing in mind that each world
would define citizenship in its own way.  (E.g., everyone 
born here is a citizen; or everyone who lives here for ten 
years is a citizen; or everyone born into certain named 
families is a citizen, no matter where born.)

*"World" really means "Imperial member state," and could
be an entire star system or a nation on a balkanized
planet.

I can\'t abide by making Imperial citizens out of
every sentient being that just happens to be in the
Imperium. That makes every Vargr corsair band that lands
on Pixie or Jesedipere for raiding or carousing into
Imperial citizens. In my Imperium the law is more or less
as follows:

Every sentient being born in the Imperium may become an
Imperial citizen.  

For species who can track biological parentage, those
beings born of parents who are all Imperial citizens need
do nothing and are automatically Imperial citizens.  Those
born of parents at least one of whom is not an Imperial
citizen are dual citizens of the Imperium and the parent\'s
state until the age of majority, at which point they much
choose.  Treaties between the Imperium and the other
recognized states further define this dual citizenship
issue.

For species who do not track parentage (e.g., Hivers),
unique rules apply.  For example, a Hiver enclave in the
Imperium (like the one in Australia) might apply for
recognition as an Imperial member state (or it might just
apply to Terra for permission to organize itself under
Terran law) and for Imperial citizenship for each of its members
and all offspring born in the enclave.  Many of the
offspring would be conceived during the handshaking part of
visits from the Hiver Federation, but they would still be
Imperial citizens.  

N.B.: Terran law might prohibit non-humans from becoming
citizens, so the Hivers might be citizens of the Imperium,
but not of any world.  

Documentation:  Travellers within the Imperium need a 
passport from at least one world (one may legitimately be a 
citizen of more than one world of the Imperium; that\'s a 
matter of local law) to pass local customs at each member 
state.  One need not be a citizen of a member state to have 
a passport properly issued:  Each Hiver in the example 
above has a special Terran passport that notes that the 
Hiver is a permanent resident of Terra.  Some member states 
may require visas (permission to enter) for entry as well.  
In order to qualify for various governmental programs of, or 
even to work in, a member state, one must show documents 
providing citizenship or other qualification under local 
law.

Travellers returning to the Imperium from outside its
borders must show an Imperial passport (often just an
Imperial stamp in their member state passport) at Imperial
customs.  Most non-Imperial states require non-citizens to 
show a passport, and possibly a visa, at customs upon 
entry.  

The Imperium does not require exit visas, nor do most 
member states. 

The citizenship of beings born in the Imperium to
diplomats from non-Imperial states is governed by treaty.

> And, umm, what exactly are the rights of a citizen of
> the Third Imperium?  If I remember correctly, the
> Imperium is actually a massive trade federation of
> politically independent worlds: the Imperial Government
> actually controls the space between the stars, not the
> worlds themselves.

Imperial citizens have two sets of rights:  collective and
individual.  The collective right is primarily the right
to collective self-determination.  For example, once the
chirpers on Vanejen were determined to be sentient (see
Alien Realms), they were entitled to diplomatic relations,
secure borders, etc. (I say "etc." because the law is 
necessarily vague:  The chirpers, once recognized as 
Imperial citizens, were entitled to whatever they could get 
the Imperium to give them, which surely focussed on 
protection from the humans of Vanejen.)  They were also 
presumably made subject to the draft.

This collective right is essential to the structure of the
Imperium:  it is what allows every Imperial member state
to have its own culture, law, political system, religions,
languages, armed forces, currencies, etc.

Individual civil rights are the rights of individuals
against the Imperium -- except for the prohibition on
slavery, these rights can\'t be asserted against Imperial
member states.  The Imperium grants basic due process,
i.e., notice and a hearing before Imperial action that
results in some deprivation to the individual.  Due
process extends in obvious directions -- trial by a jury
of one\'s peers, public laws, opportunity to appeal, notice
of Ministerial rulemaking, notice of interdictions, etc.  
Note that these due process rights apply to fictitious 
citizens like corporations, not just to individual 
sentients.  (Lawyers admitted to the Imperial bar have 
plenty of work to do.)

Slavery -- the ownership of sentient beings like property
-- is also prohibited in the Imperium (because it\'s bad for
the peace of the realm to have slave-raiders attacking
weaker member states).  This is the only Imperial civil 
right that applies to Imperial member states.

Imperial law recognizes certain "inadvertent" or
"accidental" civil rights of Imperial citizens.  For
example, Imperial regulation of expression has been
limited to prohibiting lese majeste (impugning the honor
of a superior noble by falsehood), perjury to any Imperial
body (e.g., the Moot or any Ministry or court), disclosure
of official secrets, and the like.  Thus the Imperium has
inadvertently left its citizens free to speak and to report 
the news.  Although the Emperor has the power to restrict 
freedom of speech and the press, doing so would violate 
custom.  The Emperor\'s subordinates would never violate 
customs followed by the Emperor.  Religion, family 
organization, property allocation, and the like are similar 
"accidental" rights.  

> In this view, the government, nobility and Navy should
> strictly concern themselves with keeping the trade lanes
> open, protecting the rights of traders and perhaps
> encouraging economic development.  I can see how a set
> of rights would be drawn up for merchants, and to people
> on government business. But why did the Imperium - from
> it\'s very beginning - grant rights to everyone within
> the Imperium?  

See supra for a discussion of why citizenship isn\'t granted
to "everyone within the Imperium."  The breadth of Imperial
protection was the carrot part of the carrot-and-stick
applied during the Pacification Campaigns that created the
modern Imperium.  The message then was, the Imperium will
protect you from your neighbors and leave you alone to
live as you want.  After the Long Night, that was very
attractive.

> I mean, yes it\'s generous, but it\'s a massive increase
> in workload!  Moreover, there\'s a vast number of
> political, philosophical and religious philosophies
> within the Imperium: how do the basic Imperial rights of
> any citizen (say, at a guess, the right to a fair trial)
> interact with a lawless world?  Or a totalitarian
> dictatorship?  Or even your standard, vanilla-flavoured
> Impersonal Bureaucracy?

Imperial rights don\'t apply against member states, except 
the prohibition on slavery (which affects interstellar 
relations).  So the workload doesn\'t increase.
 
> Idea: the Imperium isn\'t the miminalist government I
> always thought of it.  Well then, what is it for besides
> trade and shared security?

No, I stick to the minimalist approach.

> 
> And how do these rights interact with other interstellar
> governments, ie. 
> The Zhodani Consulate Does the local
> Zho ambassator have the right to be psionic?  And surely
> he isn\'t an Imperial citizen, simply because he crossed
> the Border? 
> The Solomani Confederation (which doesn\'t
> offically exist!) 
> The Hierate (which does, but is not as
> important as the 29 clans), The Hive Federation (how
> does Imperial law handle the right to manipulate?) 
> The
> Two Thousand worlds (how does the local embassy deal
> with Imperial citizens who happen to be carnivores?  Get
> the centaurs to expell him, rather than kill him?)
> Imperial Client States (What exactly can an Imperial
> Citizen do in a Client state that he can\'t do in a
> non-aligned world?)

Relations with interstellar governments and their envoys
are a matter of treaty, which are left to the referee\'s 
discretion.

--Glenn Goffin
