>From some experience messing with these numbers, I\'m willing to make a
completely off-the-cuff guess of a quadrillion credits or so, plus or
minus a factor of ten.  Let\'s see....

A lower limit can be guessed from one of Hans\'s recent TML sigs:

>        "This gives a possible range of 56 to 178 starships
>         total  in the three Terran starport facilities,  a
>         believable quantity for such a star system."

This probably made it to his sig block because it seems a bit...uh...
small.  But let\'s run with it.  Assume:
  * 120 ships on average at all type-A starport systems
  * Each ship is player-scaled; about 400-600 tons, worth MCr 100.
  * All the ports in the Imperium carry the equivalent of, say, 
    5000 class-A ports; this figure includes ships in transit.
  Then all this shipping is worth sixty trillion credits.  Assume
  chartered companies own just over eighty percent of it, or fifty 
  trillion credits worth.  Two percent of *just these ships* is
  a trillion credits.  If the average ship is a bulk freighter of
  MCr 10000 value and maybe fifty thousand tons, then two percent
  is a hundred trillion credits, at these traffic levels.
  
How about high-end?  Using (or misusing) the official rules, both
Derek Wildstar and I have tried to come up with estimates of the
Imperial GNP, and our results came within an order of magnitude of
each other.  Derek used a sophisticated approach; he ran the sector 
data files through a computer programmed with certain rules from
first edition Striker, shipyard rules from TCS, and the exchange
rate table.  I used the colony rules in _World Tamers\' Handbook_, 
treating the Imperium as a single HiPop world of tech-12 (AvgStellar) 
and a population of 15.77 trillion (from an old Travellers\' Digest 
article).

Derek figured Imperial GNP was just under a quarter of a quintillion
credits.  My figures originally came to over half a quintillion, but 
I didn\'t assume that I was working with tech-12, starport-B average
credits, and Derek *did* do trade table conversions.  So, to be fair,
let\'s reduce my guess by 20% to convert to tech-15, starport-A, hard
Imperial credits.  I\'m only a factor of two bigger than Derek here.  
That range is probably about as accurate an estimate as we\'re likely
to get.  In any case, two percent of annual production (not assets)
is just short of ten quadrillion credits. 

Whew.  Now, a limited-liability Imperial Charter is only required
for businesses that directly engage in interstellar commerce, so
strictly planetary companies that only ship off-world don\'t need
one.  And corporations that are pre-Imperial or have bought a pre-
Imperial chartered company, get grandfathered in, like SuSAG did.
So a quadrillion credits or so seems like a reasonable guess.

If that isn\'t bad enough, the Hortalez family may be *richer* than
the Imperial Household.  The Alkhalikoi dynasty owns about two-thirds
of a megacorporation in aggregate, a third of it in the Zirunkariish
insurance house.  The Hortalez family owns three-fourths of Hortalez
et Cie, which in turn owns in aggregate the equivalent of *two* 
megacorporations, in addition to any other corporate assets.  I
wonder what they pay regional sector managers.... :)

