    'topic' => 'Traveller Fusion',
    'body' => 'CNO fusion has been proposed again recently as the standard CT-MT fusion 
(including a very well-thought description by Duncan Law-Green). 
I would like to express some skepticism on this. CNO fusion has a stronger
temperature dependence than the p-p fusion occurring on the SUN and
require significantly higher temperatures. Since the hydrogen plasma
is "contaminated" by CNO nuclei equipartition will tend to lower
its temperature pushing it below the ignition value. Of course thermal
losses of this kind are less problematic  in a star but may be very
serious in a man-made plasma (cfr e.g. the very serious energy losses
due to helium and impurities in present day Tokamaks). My best bet is
that p-p fusion will be easier to achieve in a controlled way. Note also
that by modifying those principles one could try to achieve 3 alpha or
Carbon fusion getting more energies from the same mass of fuel. These
are certainly hard to achieve but we should not think in terms of TL 9
technologies but TL 15!

Years ago in the old TML after a long debate it was proposed to have
p-p in starships and D+He3 in portable generators (to avoid the problems
of shielding from fast neutrons). This is also an interesting solution.

above all these considerations lies the shadow of the ridicoulously low
efficiencies of fusion in MT tables. Reconciling that with any sensible
scheme is going to be pretty hard....

    Cheers,
       Max
