    'body' => '

Alun Moon wrote regarding fusion powerplants:

>   How they work.
> 	The fussion power plant, uses a magnetic bottle to contain the 
> fussion plasma.  The fussion reaction chain is similar to the H-N-O-C 
> chains in stellar fussion.  This is so my plants can use unrefined fuel 
> straight from the tanks.
> 	The manoeuver drive, uses a mix of waste products from the 
> fussion plant, and raw fuel itself.  These are mixed and fed to an MHD 
> rocket.  The mixing of the fuel and fussion waste produces an ionised 
> plasma mix, this is accellerated by the MHD coils and vented out of the 
> exaust.
> Alun
> ----
> 					A.J.Moon@newcastle.ac.uk
> 					http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~n384648/


I have never seen a reference to a MHD coil driving the plasma. If 
anything I would think it would be the other way around. The plasma 
thrust could force its way though an MHD coil to produce power. 

If I am missing some basic concept let me know. 

What would the exhaust of a fusion drive consist of? I remember that 
there was some discussion on how destructive the exhaust could be within 
an atmosphere. It seems that smaller amounts of plasma be used for thrust 
when within an atmosphere. Put the thrust though a diffuser ( Sort of a 
giant hair drier ) and it could be used for lift.

Again, if this concept lacking something basic, please let me know.


TTFN,

Glenn



