  {
    'body' => 'Hans Rancke and Steve Bonneville have been discussing
total profit of LIC corporations.  Hans last wrote: 

>But that\'s not really the essense of the matter. what
>seems almost incredible to me is that the yearly profits
>(not the income) of all LIC corporations is enough to
>support the population that creates the wealth _127 times
>over_. What do the corporations DO with all that wealth?
>Stuff it away in a sock? 

They probably do what contemporary corporations do with it
-- invest some in themselves, invest some in other
entities, and pay a big chunk of it to their top
executives, who consume some, hoard some, and invest some.
In addition, the form of that wealth is not necessarily
cash or other liquid assets.  A good amount of it is in
land and starships, which use a lot for maintenance and
aren\'t simple to trade. A lot of it is probably in
intangibles, too, like patents, which are also difficult to 
trade because they\'re difficult to value.

I don\'t know what the figures are for U.S. corporations\'
profits versus the cost of supporting the total population,
but I remember reading earlier this year something to the
effect that most CEOs of big U.S. corporations receive
total compensation well in excess of their companies\' total
payroll.  I\'m not sure if it was in the Wall Street Journal 
or The Nation, but it may have been in both.  

--Glenn
