    'index' => 'ab807',
    'body' => 'Steven Bonneville <bonnevil@itlabs.umn.edu> writes:

>There\'s some interesting place names in the Marches that may have
>meaning in Latin.  Regina means queen, and it\'s a beautiful world 
>that\'s very powerful in the sector.  Mora means delay or stop-off, 
>and Mora is the gateway to the sector, a place settled as a base
>for ships to stop-over as they enter the Marches.  Vilis means 
>cheap or worthless -- but the Sword Worlders don\'t think so, and 
>have gone to war with the Imperium (another Latin word!) over it.

Knowing that Vilani has the phonology (roughtly) of Sumerian I decided
to see if any of the Vilani names we know have real meanings. Sure
enough, they do. "Dingir" is a Sumerian word for "deity"; in Akkadian
inscriptions the sign for "dingir" (or the equivalent word in
Akkadian) is prefixed to deity names. "Shuruppak" was an actual city
in Mesopotamia. "Enlugal", Vland\'s capital city\'s name, contains the
element "lugal", a Sumerian word for "king". There are probably more
that escape me right now.

-- 
Erich Schneider  erich@bush.cs.tamu.edu  http://bush.cs.tamu.edu/~erich
