Well, I  think David Summers has hit on the trillion dollar question re:
Traveller. It is the question of whether or not one is able to travel faster
than the speed of light ( or very close to the speed of light without
incurring the effects of relativity) in the Traveller universe. The
playability of Traveller relys on one being able to travel vast distances in
space while having the same amount of time pass on board the craft,on the
world of departure, and on the destination world. In effect, the traveller
universe is a Newtonian universe in which astronomical bodies are separated
only by distance while Relativity tells us that actually the only thing
keeping worlds apart in space is time. The common Imperial timeline is a
playability feature that is a physical impossibility. The shiptime kept by
the ships computer would be the only time of importance. 

I therefore run my games on the premise that jump drives are a combination
burn and field generating drive. The field generated alters the dimensions
of space-time creating a refined and controllable worm-hole like feature
through which the craft can travel. The field creates a situation in which
the point of departure and destination can locally co-exist for the jump
travel time. 

The reason for keeping ship travel time to seven days seems a little
arbitrary to me, always has. I can see no reason why, using my own vision of
the jump drive, a ship can\'t have a sufficiently advanced jump drive that is
able to generate a field that will momentarily make the points of departure
and destination co-exist exactly making the ship travel time zero.
I also see no reason why,and consider it most likely that,  at the lower end
of the starship drive technology spectrum there would be a starship drives
of the purely  conventional burn type as outlined in FF&S. These ships,
however, could not take part in the space opera that is the Imperium or the
Coalition etc. They would slowly accelorate to close to the speed of light
and would be destined to never return to their home again due to the effects
of relativity. These ships would take years to reach their nearest
destinations.

In my vision of jump drives there is nothing random involved. The navigation
and creation of the temporary worm-hole is tightly calculated. In FF&S there
is a descriptioin of randomly occuring worm-holes of various natures. These
can be seen as the naturally occuring variety of what my jump drive
generators create. One could even speculated that some of these apparently
naturally occuring worm-holes are in fact the result of illformed generator
fields of misjumped craft.
The potential for misjump is great and the possible causes many. The burn
drive could fail trapping the ship in the wormhole longer than expected. The
generator may fail, misshaping the field or collapsing mid-flight (possibly
leaving the craft trapped in a mobius loop or some such) or the navicomputer
may fail. The effects are equaly many and thankfully still left to the
discretion of the Referee.

If the jump drive failled completely, as in the situation David asked about,
I would say that the field collapsed and the ship would be left drifting on
a fixed vector in free space light years from a world of any kind. The
manuever drive would not be sufficient to accelorate the ship to anything
close to the speed of light for a conventional flight to safety, so one may
as well get new characters. There is nothing out here but space hulks and
even they are millions of kms apart.

Its been fun giving you the run down on how I like to run my Traveller
universe re: stardrives. Hope it helps.


