    'index' => 'ab831',
    'topic' => 'Moties and Other Literary Inspirations',
    'body' => 'In XBoat 409, David Jaques-Watson, replying to David J Golden 
replying to David Jaques-Watson wrote:

>>        Sounds a lot like the Moties from "The Mote In God\'s Eye," by Niven
>>and Pournelle. The Moties developed a Mediator sub-species to negotiate
>>between Masters.

>Let\'s face it, the Droyne _are_ the Moties. Both have a rigid caste system
>and different "sub-species" (Worker, Warrior, Technician, whatever). Many
>things in Traveller can be traced almost directly to s-f novels, for
>example much of H. Beam Piper\'s work (the Sword Worlds, the "Space
Vikings"),
>Niven, Pournelle, Heinlein (eg "Starship Trooper"). Some s-f novels can be
>traced to Traveller (for example, in my opinion, David Drake\'s "Hammer\'s
>Slammers", "The Forlorn Hope", etc).

I remember that in the original GDW Hivers sourcebook, there was a specific 
statement 
by Mark Miller that the Hivers were based on a combination of Niven\'s  
Puppeteers and 
the Outsiders.  Did he ever make any such comment about his other races?  I 
would be 
interested to hear about it.

I know I have always run the Droyne in a manner similar to the Moties, and I 
even went 
to the effort of creating a Watchmaker subcaste that got my PCs into big 
trouble once  
(this was the real reason Andory and Candory were Red Zones).  I was
pleasantly 
surprised to see that others were thinking along the same lines.

As for Drake\'s work, I don\'t think it is based on Traveller technology or 
background, but his 
Hammer\'s Slammers stuff definitely reads like a good (violent) Traveller 
campaign.

Steve Charlton
scharlto@avalon.com
scharlto@rtd.com
My employers have no opinions about this.  Other things yes, but not this...
