rodge@cyberspace.com (Roger Sanger) wries:

 ----
What is the range of sensors, such as the sensors aboard naval
battleships?
 ----

AFAIK in CT 5 lightseconds (3 LS for civilians) tracking out to 6 LS for 
both.
In MT whatever the sensors are rated at 8-)

 ----
What are the ranges of starship weapons?
 ----

It generally seems to be taken as a few light seconds effective range at 
most.

 ----
What kind of defense is there against ships jumping in to a system
and firing immediately?
 ----

None except that the jumping ship would presumably be low on fuel and I have 
always assumed that the jump exit location is only known to within a 
considerable number of Light seconds.

 ----
Since light travels relatively slow, planet-bound targets won\'t
detect the enemy until enemy fire has already reached them (since
energy blasts also travel at the speed of light).
 ----

What about the burst of energy upon jump exit? Also not knowing precisely 
where  the jump exit point will be means some time must be spent in 
orientation and target acquisition before useful firing can take place.

 ----
What\'s to prevent a battleship from jumping-in to a system and
immediately firing its weapons at premapped planetary targets?
 ----

Uncertainty of exit points...

 ----
If they fire from far away, it could conceivably take 10 or more
minutes for the blasts to reach the planet.  By the time the planet
fires back, the attacking ships could easily jump back out of system,
or change vectors.
 ----

Light MINUTES! Thats a looong way out. I think you\'d need a bloody big focal 
array to get your lasers to do anything more than wake them up!

 ----
How do you lock-on to a target that is 10 light-seconds away, that
is continously changing vectors?
 ----

Ok. The simple answer is of course "with some difficulty" ;)

Really you don\'t lock onto the target, you lock onto the position the target 
was in 10 seconds (+ processer & weapon alignment time) ago.

 ----
How do you hit such a target?
 ----

Ok, you have the position of the target 10 seconds ago, if using passive 
sensors only you have the angular change in position relative to you, if you 
know the characteristics of the target or are using active sensors you have 
range data as well.

Using this you can determine the targets position and vector at t= -10 
seconds.
If the target doesn\'t maneouvre you can predict precisely where it will be 
when your laser beams hit it at t= +10 seconds

If you know the targets characteristics you have a limit on how much 
acceleration the target can use to change its position, if not then you are 
going to have to guess the targets potential acceleration based on the 
targets previous movement.

If the target maneouvres then its position can be anywhere in a sphere ( due 
to the fact that it would usually take an amount of time to slew the target 
ship it would actually be a cartioid like shape but a sphere is the worst 
case ) centred on the targets predicted position of a size determined by the 
targets acceration.

As light is so fast the depth of the sphere can be ignored so all you have 
to do is fire a pattern of shots over the area of the sphere\'s 
cross-section.

Your chance of hitting is determined by the number of shots fired, the size 
of the sphere of future target position and the target\'s cross-section in 
that aspect.

 ----
Subject:missiles

What about the nuclear variety?

What happens when such a missile goes off high in a planet\'s
atmosphere?

Or even a little beyond the atmosphere?
 ----

Can anyone say EMP?
Also how about killing by X-ray flux?

 ----
What sort of nukes are available by TL15?
 ----

I\'m sure I\'ve seen somewhere offficial that TL15 nukes are laser triggered, 
no fissionables...

 ----
What is a "fusion" warhead in Traveller?

Is it a form of nuke?
 ----

Well, fusion is a nuclear process so presumably......

 ----
If so, do Nuclear Dampers protect against it?
 ----

Yes, but only if they are focussed in the correct way when detonation is 
attempted.

 ----
Or is it a larger version of the plasma grenade?
 ----

Plasma grenade? What plasma grenade?

erich@bush.cs.tamu.edu (Erich Schneider) writes:

 ----
