    'topic' => 'Roger Sanger\'s questions',
    'body' => '> What is the range of sensors, such as the sensors aboard naval
> battleships?

What does "range" mean in this context?  The range of the
human eye is many light-years, because we can see stars
that far away without assistance.  Of course, we can\'t
tell much about them.

The range of passive sensors is thus basically infinite -- 
whatever energy registers on the sensor will be reported, 
but degradations for distance (as well as intervening 
stuff) will occur.

The range of active sensors, on the other hand, is the 
range beyond which the returned signal is too corrupted to 
read.  How far is that?

> What are the ranges of starship weapons?

Again, you have to divide the weapons up.  A missile will
go on forever, I suppose, but it can only accelerate until
its fuel is used up.  Then it\'ll coast at whatever speed it
achieved with its last burn.

I hope that someone more knowledgeable than me about the
physics involved will describe what happens to energy at
long ranges.  I think that ranges (effective,
half-strength, weak, ineffective, e.g.) will be defined by
how much the energy is weakened by spreading out. 

> What kind of defense is there against ships jumping in to
> a system and firing immediately?

Just counter-intelligence.  

> If they fire from far away, it could conceivably take 10
> or more minutes for the blasts to reach the planet.  By
> the time the planet fires back, the attacking ships could
> easily jump back out of system, or change vectors.

The attacker needs more like 8 hours to get ready for the 
next jump, per the Starship Operator\'s Manual, I think.  
Black globe-equipped ships are even more of a problem:  
They calculate where they\'ll enter the system in relation 
to where the targets on the planet will be when their fire 
arrives, jump, fire, activate black globe before anyone 
knows they\'re there, coast on a preset vector while getting 
ready to jump, drop black globe and fire and jump.  They 
just don\'t know whether their shots were effective or not.

> 


> How do you lock-on to a target that is 10 light-seconds
> away, that is continously changing vectors?

I thought the Predict program did that.  Oh, you mean, how 
does the Predict program work?  

> What happens when such a missile goes off high in a planet\'s
> atmosphere?

This we might think we know a little about:  It spreads 
radioactive materials into the jet stream, to the detriment 
of the ecosystem and the enemy living in the ecosystem.  If 
it\'s big enough, relative to the atmosphere, maybe it blows 
part of the atmosphere off into space, but again, I hope 
that someone with a real physics background responds.

 
> What is a "fusion" warhead in Traveller?

I think it\'s a hydrogen bomb, like we have today.  A 
fission explosion compresses hydrogen enough to get it 
begin a fusion reaction.  At higher tech levels, gravitic 
devices cause the necessary compression.

> If so, do Nuclear Dampers protect against it?

Nuclear Dampers should only protect against low-tech fusion 
bombs using fission compression.

--Glenn
