    'topic' => ' XBOAT digest 418',
    'body' => 'Rodger asks. . .

>What kind of defense is there against ships jumping in to a system
>and firing immediately?

The answer can vary between campaigns, but the general consensus from past
discussions is that Jump isn\'t *that* accurate. Canonically, Jumps are
*about* a week - some take six days, some take eight days, randomly. Even
with precise control of Jump coordinates (where you land), planets move a
lot in a couple of days, and predicting when (and in many campaigns, where)
you\'ll arrive is difficult at best.

THe result is that ships jump in and get their coordinates. They may have
some time advantage over their targets, but not as much as a pop-in,
pop-out attack like the kind you imply.

This also depends on ranges, sensor quality, and so on. I don\'t know how
canonical this is, but a system could have sensors strewn out around
strategic locations and possibly detect the new ship before it could find
it bearings and bring itself to bear.

>Since light travels relatively slow, planet-bound targets won\'t
>detect the enemy until enemy fire has already reached them (since
>energy blasts also travel at the speed of light).

True, but if ranges is short enough (even a few thousand kilometers) it\'s
likely that the ship will have been detected while traveling from the 100
diameter limit to weapons range.

>What\'s to prevent a battleship from jumping-in to a system and
>immediately firing its weapons at premapped planetary targets?

As above. You don\'t know when or where you\'ll land - pre-calc coordinates
are useful only when you get to a pre-calc location to adjust from.

>If they fire from far away, it could conceivably take 10 or more
>minutes for the blasts to reach the planet.  By the time the planet
>fires back, the attacking ships could easily jump back out of system,
>or change vectors.

Then why did yuou attack the system? That\'s just harrasment. Hit & run
might affect shipping but it won\'t win the war by itself - sooner or later
you\'ll have to land some troops, or at least station ships for space
superiority.

>How do you lock-on to a target that is 10 light-seconds away, that
>is continously changing vectors?

Try and predict where it will be in 10 seconds. I imagine that a thorough
understanding of Quantum Physics and predictability would be required. :)

>How do you hit such a target?

Perhaps targets do not engage until within more reasonable ranges.

>What happens when such a missile goes off high in a planet\'s
>atmosphere?

People say "wow, that was the most beautiful one" while waiting for the fallout.

Other questions deleted because I don\'t know the answers. Hope the rest helps.

J Roberson      est. 1973
