    'topic' => 'Space Combat (long!)',
    'body' => 'Hi there

A lot of questions from Roger Sanger!  I\'ve been playing around with
setting up rules for space combat, for my online rules page
(http://www.jb.man.ac.uk/~spe/Rules/), so here are some of my thoughts

> What is the range of sensors, such as the sensors aboard naval battleships?

Active EM sensors I restrict to about 500 000 km, or 5 000 000 km if
conditions are good.  Passive sensors can go much further; I take the
range ratings as a measure of sensitivity, although PEMS Interstellar
range refers to the ability to do astronomical measurements on nearby
stars.  I\'m also toying with the idea of resolution based on the
largest length scale of the starship; for a synthetic aperture sensor,
the resolution is roughly 57*wavelength/separation of sensor elements
(in degrees), so larger vessels can resolve things which are closer
together.  This also introduces the possibility of extended senor
booms, giving a vessel greater resolution than their size would
suggest; these booms would be more susceptable to damage in combat.

> What are the ranges of starship weapons?

I restrict my beam weapons to ranges of 50 000 km, and high energy
weapons to only 5 000 km; in my game, it is essential to get in close!
This is again because of the 57*wavelength/diameter law; any beam will
spread over a large area over fairly short distances, and infact I
think 50 000 km is pushing it (without FFS gravitic focussing magic!)
As for missiles, if you are willing to build them big enough, they can
have the range of any spaceship.  I keep my non-bay missiles to the
canonical (CT) mass of 50 kg, and fitting into 100 l storage.  I think
this gives my missiles a single-burn range equivalent to a beam
weapon.  I also make my missiles kinetic energy weapons; the HE charge
shatters the missile, allowing multiple particles a greater chance of
intercepting the target.  These things can be lethal if the relative
velocities of the launcher and the target are high, but the rocket
acceleration is sufficient to make them dangerous in any situation.  I
also have deadfall ordnance, with no rocket.  The greater final mass
leads to enhanced damage, but you aim them by pointing your ship\'s
velocity at the target!

> What kind of defense is there against ships jumping in to a system
> and firing immediately?
 (... some more stuff in a similar vein ...)

Range of beam wepons and sensors.  You can fire missiles, but as they
don\'t travel at the speed of light, the target has a chance of seeing
them coming.

>What\'s to prevent a battleship from jumping-in to a system and
>immediately firing its weapons at premapped planetary targets?

It was canonical that jump was not 100 % accurate; you cannot know
exactly how long a jump will take, or exactly where you will be.  On
interplanetary scales, a few 1000 km and a few minutes can make a big
difference to precision shooting.

> How do you lock-on to a target that is 10 light-seconds away, that
> is continously changing vectors?

You don\'t :-)

> How do you hit such a target?

You don\'t :-), or you put a wide cone of very high-velocity
heavy-metal particles in it\'s (possible) path, and wait for it to hit.


> What about the nuclear variety?

I haven\'t been able to fit nuclear missiles into my ideas yet


> What is a "fusion" warhead in Traveller?

I\'d guess this is a combined fusion-fission warhead, which uses a
fusion reaction to set-off the explosion.  I seem to remember
something about a "clean" nuke, which may have used fusion.

For an excellent, dramatised idea of interplanetary combat at long
range and high velocity, look at C. J. Cherryh\'s Rimrunner or
Hellburner or Heavy Time.  Essentially, the idea is guess where your
target is going to be when your weapons arrive, and put a lot of crap
in the way.

Sorry, v. long post!

