    'body' => 'Hiya

In regards to various messages (from Charles Collins, and also from Roger 
Sanger); I remember reading (but not where) about the situation where a 
ship jumps into the outer area of a system. Assuming that it exits 
J-space about where Jupiter would be in our system, that gives the 
incoming ship an enormous intelligence-gathering ability.

Sure it\'s not all guns blazing stuff, but this sort of mission is 
*exactly* what is needed immediately before dispatching such a mission. 
It reduces the inteligence estimation error to a mere giggle (only a week 
old) rather then being ridiculously out of date. Whats more, it is highly 
likely that the spy ship will have exactly no exciting encounters out 
there (especially if it does not have to refuels which limits matters 
greatly.)

The reason for such a quiet mission is exactly the same as was mentioned 
as a problem predicting an enemy ships movements. This time the 
light-speed lag is working in your favour. If a ship jumps into the outer 
reaches of the system, and then accumulates data, it takes anywhere from 
eight hours to several days for the light from the ships emergence from 
jump to make it to the planet. The planet, being stationary, and emitting 
EMS signals for a lot longer than that is available on sensors of the spy 
ship immediately (admittedly some hours old.)

By the time the emergence flare has reached the planet, the ship is 
making ready to jump (home this time).

In regards to shooting at a ship 10 or more light seconds away, that is 
an awesome area to cover with lasers, and I would guess impossible to 
fill with shrapnel (most ships would not carry the amount of ordnance 
necessary and still have reloads). I personally would wait until they 
were closer. The amount of energy, mass, and stress expended falls 
according to the inverse square law. At half the range, it is a quarter 
of the problem.

I hope this answers more questions than it raises ;-)

Regards
A P Madden (amadden@pcug.org.au)
