    'year' => 1995,
    'index' => 'ab873',
    'body' => '>Date: Sun, 22 Oct 95 18:51:01 PDT
>To: xboat@MPGN.COM
>Subject: No planetary defense?
>
>What are the ranges of starship weapons?
>
>What kind of defense is there against ships jumping in to a system
>and firing immediately?

Jumping to within 100 planatery diameters is dangerous.

Planetary defense ships are likely to be in the near vicinity of the
planet.

So we can take the ship to be not *too* close, and not immune to
counter-attack.

>Since light travels relatively slow, planet-bound targets won\'t 
>detect the enemy until enemy fire has already reached them (since
>energy blasts also travel at the speed of light).  

A ship can\'t hit an ENTIRE planet in one shot.  The fraction of the
planet hit by energy weapons in the first few minutes of combat is so
small as to be "zero".  Unless your hypothetical planet has only one
small, localized target, it\'s going to have warning.

Energy weapons are unlikley to be useful against targets shrouded in
atmosphere (which scatters lasers, and is even more effective against
other beam weapons).  Meson guns, maybe, depending on how you view
their "magic penetration" as working.

So that must have been one small, localized target on a vacuum world.

On the *surface* of a vacuum world.  It\'s a lot easier to put 100\' of
rock between you and the surface than it is to put 100\' of rock around
an attacking warship, and according to the armour strengths of buffered
planetoids, even a small amount of rock is apparently good armour.

>What\'s to prevent a battleship from jumping-in to a system and
>immediately firing its weapons at premapped planetary targets?

Essentially, nothing.  But beam weapons aren\'t very effective, it\'s a
big world, and military targets will be dug in.  You could wreak havoc
on a number of civilian targets on a vacuum world----but given the risk
ov micro-meteroites on such a world, and the lack of scenery, even
civilian targets are likely to be dug-in on a vacuum world.

Missile attacks are a more realistic way of attacking a world.  A ship
could jump in and launch a wave of missiles.

>If they fire from far away, it could conceivably take 10 or more 
>minutes for the blasts to reach the planet.  By the time the planet
>fires back, the attacking ships could easily jump back out of system,
>or change vectors.

High guard implies that jumping takes 40 minutes if power-plant
capacity is equal to the jump attempted and 20 minutes if power-plant
capacity is twice the jump attempted.

So we can suppose that a ship with a power plant capable of supporting
jump-6 could execute a jump-1 in about seven minutes.

A full combat round is twenty minutes, so in 7 minutes the ship should
only be allowed to do about one-third damage (either firing one-third
of its weapons, or firing all weapons for one-third damage, depending
on the ref wants to interpet it).

You would have to be using a fleet of overwelming force for one-third
of one round of firing to be more than a nuisance to a planet.  And you
can only do this nuisance attack once every two weeks with your ship.

It\'s an interesting tactic, but I don\'t think it "breaks" anything in
the Traveller universe.  If you want to do a real attack, you\'re still
going to have to hang around for the consequences.

What it would probably be is a terrorist tactic, not a military
tactic.  It\'s not going to hurt a world much in real terms, but it will
sure get the citizens scared and very ticked off.

>What about the nuclear variety?
>
>What happens when such a missile goes off high in a planet\'s
>atmosphere?
>
>Or even a little beyond the atmosphere?

I assume you\'re refering to NEMP (if I got the accronym right----Nuclear
Electro-Magnetic Pulse).  NEMP is most effective against wire-based
power distribution and communication (traditional copper-wire telephone
networks, cable T.V., and the entire power grid).  The wires act as
antenna, pick up too much power, and the networks are out of commission
until multiple overload-failures are repaired (days).

I doubt this would do anything to TL11+ communications; running copper
wire for communication is a 1900\'s solution, not a 1995 solution.  If
we didn\'t have so much invested in copper wiring, cellular radio would
be the dominant solution today.  Presumably even more so for
higher-tech societies.  And where wire still makes sense, it will be
fiber-optic, not copper.

Losing the power-grid... a society that can build fusion plants and fit
them into a 100ton space ship isn\'t going to need today\'s model of huge
power plants serving customers hundreds of miles away.  Again, at
higher tech levels, the target presumably no longer exists.

In addition to the target (large grid of metal wires) not existing at
higher tech levels, the technology should be much better at handling
overloads that do occur.

So at a guess, I\'d say at TL11 or higher, NEMP has no effect on a
world.

At TLs below telephone and power distribution, NEMP has nothing to
hurt.

In the mid-range TL\'s, NEMP could be very effective.  Military
equipment and installations will be unaffected (hardening against such
effects is standard) but civilians could be without power or
communication for days.

On inhospitable worlds, one could expect life-support to be as heavily
shielded as military----for one thing some natural causes can mimic the
same effects in milder terms.  You\'re probably not going to direcly
kill many people with a NEMP attack.

----

You don\'t need a nuclear weapon for this.  A nuclear weapon lets you
cover a continent with one blast, but if you have a more specific
target you can do this with conventional explosives.  Form a powerful,
small electromagnet, then use a conventional explosive to explode
(outwards) the coils of the magnet.

The effect is a very powerful magnetic pulse that has all the above effects
in the nearby area (few miles), plus the local EM field levels within
a few hundred meters will be strong enough to destroy electronics that
would be immune to NEMP\'s lower, but more widespread, effects.

This requires at least cryogenic cooling with today\'s technology to get
a strong enough electromagnet, making it an exotic idea without much
real application----you could use a convential explosive of the same
size as the cryo unit to outright destroy the object instead of frying
it).  At TL\'s where high-current superconductors exist, this becomes a
useful weapon.

Since this is a smaller, but more intense effect, it will work against
higher TL\'s (power grids as small as a block might be effected), and
probably almost any TL level of electronics within a building-sized
area would be destroyed.

>What sort of nukes are available by TL15?

Big nukes, little nukes, dial-a-yield nukes, extremely clean nukes,
filthy dirty nukes, high-radiation, low-blast nukes, high-blast,
low-radiation nukes...

What did you want?  :-).

Modern TL is capable of all of the above variations to a limited
extent.  TL15 should remove all of the "limited" from the variations.

Probably add some more exotic variations, like shaped-charge nukes.

Why not tell us what effect you wanted, and we\'ll talk about what TL
seems appropriate.

- Paul Colley
