    'from' => 'Andy Lilly',
    'body' => 'In x419, Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> asked about the
Traveller Chronicle (TTC) - does it have enough CT stuff in it.

Well, I write stuff for TTC and try to make all my stuff as generic
(CT/MT/TNE) as possible. Everything I do can be set in TTC\'s Far Frontiers
sector which, having experienced little change throughout the Rebellion and
Virus periods, is fairly easy to adapt to any setting. So, CT content in TTC
is fairly good and one can always adapt ideas from TNE (sound of xboaters
hissing and spitting).

If you want to see some examples of TTC work, point your web-browser at:

http://eeyore.lv-hrc.nevada.edu/~indy/traveller.html

The Rock Called Jade adventure in Issue 7 is an example of a fairly generic
sort of scenario which could be adapted to any era.

>...I was wondering 
>what ever became of this idea for a Traveller Fanzine.  I think it would 
>be a great idea.  I would personally pledge one article a month...

Well, I know how much time it takes me to write stuff for TTC. I, too, have
millions of ideas, but my fingers can only type so fast... Therefore, the
success of any Net Fanzine depends on the persistence of at least 2 or 3
prolific writers who are willing to constantly produce work for no reward
(except Net recognition). PLUS any such venture should not compromise the
operation of current systems, i.e. xboat and TML; if you\'re producing stuff
and want to distribute it free, just shove it into xboat/TML - you don\'t
need a separate fanzine. If you ask for contributions to yourself and then
pass it on, then unless you\'re careful work gets lost and you edit out what
_you_ don\'t like... whereas if everything goes straight to xboat/TML then
some of the stuff you didn\'t like might really be the biz\' for someone else.

Use the above as a positive push rather than a negative downer: my
experience is that a lot of people talk about ideas but very few of them
ever get as far as writing them down. And fewer still get beyond their first
such article. So you need to have the persistence to keep going at it. Hell,
I regard myself as a sci-fi writer, having written several Traveller-based
books. That\'s a big undertaking, but that\'s nothing compared to the fight to
actually get something published... I\'m still waiting after 3 years... GDW
didn\'t like my stuff because it wasn\'t copied straight out of the TNE source
books (they went for Death of Wisdom instead - look how well that was
received [not])... so, anyone out there got a friend in publishing?
:-(

Andy

