    'body' => '> Since light travels relatively slow, planet-bound targets won\'t 
Surly not!  To what is light relatively slow?

Sensors, Fire Control and Weapons
=================================
Based on my notes for CT.  For the Scout and Navy ships 
Sensor detection range 2light seconds, tracking is out to 3light 
seconds.  Civ ships detect at 1/2 light second.
I take this to be the capabilities of the fire control sensors.

In the 6 seconds for the light to reach the scout, and the laser fire 
to return, a ship doing 6g can change its projected position by up to 
1000m.  At 3light seconds this is 1 part in a million.  (At 1g this 
becomes 180m)

Obviously, the output of the engines can be detected, so the size of 
this circle can be predicted.  As Charles pointed out.  This is what 
the suit of Predict programs do, along with Gunner experience.  Then 
the Manoeuvre-Evade programs, and a good Pilot set up patterns trying 
to make the position in the circle as difficult to predict as 
possible.  The process though is mainly statistical mechanics.

The laser and beam weapons would be configured to be most effective 
at these sort of ranges.
Missiles on the other hand, have a much larger "circle of 
probability", to aim at due to the longer flight times.  But they do 
have their own sensors and propulsion for terminal guidance.

I expect space combat would look a little like modern ASW.  You know 
where the target WAS, and where she MIGHT be.  Your weapons can 
either strike at range, where you are guessing more, but allow no 
evasion (lasers).  Or close and use their own guidance, but could be 
dogged (missiles).

Or course the ships will have other sensors, with longer ranges.  
After all the Type-S can detect stars and Gas giants 2pc away!

Though the above might change for capital ships.  Though longer 
ranges needs more guess work.  I expect 3light seconds is an optimum.

Nukes
=====
Most missiles will only go up to about 10kton yield (turret 
launched), so letting on off in the upper atmosphere will cause EMP 
effects but little else.  Then their are the "Big Boys" with bay 
launched weapons!

Fusion nukes at early tech levels will have a fission initiator, so 
could be countered by Nuclear Dampers.  Higher tech levels will have 
laser initiators so Nuclear Dampers will be less effective.  At 
higher tech levels the initiation would become better (smaller!), and 
the overall weapon size would come down.

Jump(Pop)-Up attacks
====================
You just can\'t do it!
You cannot guarantee the accuracy of the exit point in space-time, (I 
can\'t remember the errors).  Or even possibly your exit orientation.  
It\'d take several minutes to sort this lot out, and target the 
planet.

Firing from 10 light minutes away!!
You couldn\'t deliver enough coherent energy to give a Nat sunburn!

You would then take a few hours to reset the jump out of the system, 
assuming of course that you had the fuel to do so!



Alun
