    'body' => 'Tom Trelenberg posed an interesting question:  
 
> I was wondering if anyone knows of any rules concerning
> emergency landings of unstreamlined ships.  I understand
> that the designs of such ships so not enable them to
> support their own weight as in a landing, but is there
> any way to get such a ship through an atmosphere (and
> then perhaps have it "hover" on its drives--assuming they
> were not the emergency--as the ship is evacuated.)   I am
> trying to put together an adventure where I would very
> much like it to be possible; however, I will find
> another way if such a landing is strictly forbidden
> (Captain, I canna change the laws of physics).

Well, there are unstreamlined ships and there are 
unstreamlined ships.  High Guard recognizes nine hull
configurations:

needle/wedge		streamlined
cone			streamlined
cylinder		partially streamlined
close structure		partially streamlined (e.g., Gazelle)
sphere			partially streamlined (e.g., Broadsword)
flattened sphere	streamlined
dispersed structure	not streamlined
planetoid		not streamlined
buffered planetoid	not streamlined

Partially streamlined hulls can refuel at gas giants, so
presumably can withstand any atmospheric stress involved in
the unorthodox maneuver that you describe.  

As to a dispersed structure, I as a referee would rules 
that it cannot withstand the stress of atmospheric entry, 
and would be torn apart when trying to enter the 
atmosphere, not matter how slowly or carefully the crew 
tries to do so.

Planetoids and buffered planetoids should not suffer as
much meteorism as asteroids upon entry, because they can
use their maneuvre drives to slow themselves down.  

The use of repulsors to ameliorate the effects of 
atmospheric entry stress is worth considering -- could a 
ship repel the atmosphere below it, descending in 
essentially a vaccuum, until it gets close to the surface 
of the planet and stops its descent?

I don\'t consider gravitational stress to be an issue for
any ships, because they are all built to withstand their
own accelerations, which generally exceed the
gravitational force of any planet where they would want to
land their crews.  

--Glenn
