    'index' => 'ab912',
    'body' => 'Okay, I\'ve got a problem here which may stir up some debate:  How do grav 
plates work?  Obviously, there can be no answer of a purely scientific 
nature, but it\'s nice to have a fictional operating principle for 
technobabbling purposes.  

Here\'s my major concern:  Why do grav plates not exert their forces on 
other bodies outside the ship?  For instance, if you turn on a 1G floor 
field, then why does it not pull on the planet below you with a force of 
1G?  If you\'re using a 6G field to compensate for an average fighter\'s 
acceleration, you should throw whole solar systems into disarray!

The problem arises because gravity is (according to Einstein anyway) not 
really a "force" with quanta at all.  Gravity consists of bends in 
space-time into which bodies "fall".  Therefore, to create a 1G floor 
field, you\'ve got to create a bend in space-time equivalent to that made 
by a size 8 planet.  And this bend would have far-reaching effects.

I may  have a way of explaining away this problem, but I\'d like to see 
what other people say.  My explanation goes like this:  Traveller grav 
technology  cannot really produce attractive gravity, rather it only 
produces a repulsive kind of "contra-gravity" (otherwise, why no tractor 
beams?).  Negative gravity, by the way, is perfectly allowable by modern 
physics/cosmology, though it has never been observed.  Traveller gravitic 
systems (inertial compensators, repulsors, etc.) work by producing 
anti-gravitons which push on things.  A "floor field" is actually in the 
ceiling pushing down (this effect would be indistinguishable from the 
opposite set up).  The anti-gravitons, because they repulse one another, 
have a very rapidly diminishing effectiveness.  Instead of their force 
dropping with the square of the distance, it diminishes with the square 
of the square of the distance (or distance to the fourth).

So, what do you think?

