    'id' => '<2agkDD8w165w@krypton.rain.com>',
    'topic' => 'sneak attacks',
    'body' => 'Ok, let\'s look at this carefully. 

Folks say there\'s a "flare" when you jump in (must be a MT thing, I
don\'t recall it from CT). There *has* to be a range limit on this, or
folks would be sending out salvage crews to pick up the ships that
misjumped and landed a few thousand AU short...

So, that means it *is* possible to jump into the outer system
undetected, though it may be *way* out there.

By some strange coincidence <g> this is one of the better locations for
undetected refueling. You\'re in one of the cometary halo areas if you
are more than a hundred or so AU out. So careful observuing with a
one meter or so telescope for a day or three will give you tyhe
locations of some "nearby" bodies, and they are almost guaranteed to be
icy (ice largely, if not entirely made of various ices).

Bingo, supply some heat, and you\'ve got a something to feed thru the
fuel refining gear.

And given that these bodies are likely to be *kilometers* in diameter,
you\'ve got all the fuel a clandestine listening post could want. Plus a
nice "secret" refueling base. Nobody but the skipper anfd the
navigators (and maybe sensor techs) will have any idea *where* the ship
is. The Star will just be another star in the sky. :-)

Locating such a base is next to impossible. There\'s just too many cubic
AUs to search.

Now we come to the "hit and run" attack. 

Most likely is a planned "Pearl Harbor" type attack. Either to get a
quick surrender or to just plain pulverize an important world so that
you don\'t have to worry about it.

If I was doing it, I\'d look for a Ceres sized body that was still
fairly icy. On such a body it wouldn\'t be impossible to bore a tunnel
completely thru it. Nor would it be impossible to "nudge" the rotation
until it was lined up favorably (orbital motion hardly counts when you
are dealing with something that far out).

So, we now have a 1000km long tunnel. We build a mass-driver into it.
At 100 gee, the projectile will be moving at roughly 45 km/s when it
exits. At 1000 gee, it\'ll be moving around 140 km/s. We could build
such a driver. At higher TLs, higher accelerations ought to be
possible. 10k gee gives 450 km/s, 100k gives 1400, and 1 million gives
4500 (1.5% of c). 

Even a 1 ton projectile at those velocities is equivalent to a *large*
nuke. And a 1 ton *mass*, stealthed projectile made of say, nickel
iron, will be all of 125 *liters* (that\'s .125 kl). That\'s a sphere 38
cm radius (or 15 inches). Or to put it another way, it\'s about the size
of an 18 inch shell.

Terminal guidance *is* possible, even with *current* electronics. And
detecting this puppy could be *very* difficult. I seriously doubt it
could be detected before it got within a few light seconds. Which means
that backtracking it would be a *bitch*. You only have a ridiculously
small portion of the track to extrapolate from. You couldn\'t get within
billions of km.

Bad news is that it\'d take 4000 days from 100 AU at 45 km/s. Only 1000
at 140km/s. But at 450 it drops to 400 days, at 1400 it\'s 100 days, and
at 4500 gives 40 days. 

A major undertaking? Sure. It\'s a big project. But it\'s not an
*unreasonable* project. And take another look at that 1 million gee
version. At those speeds you are talking about a planet wrecker. And
the whole inner system covers such a small arc that aiming can be
handled by course corrections *after* the projectile leaves the
launcher.

Oh yeah, at 1.5% of c, if you can detect it 30 light seconds out
(bloody unlikely), the dectection message will get to you 1970 seconds
(32 min, 50 sec) before the projectile hits.  If you can only detect to
10 light seconds, you get 10 minutes, 50 seconds of warning. And if you
only detect it at 1 light second, you have 65 seconds to say your
prayers.

Someone mentioned reaction to the massdriver attack on the Narn
homeworld in last week\'s Babylon 5 episode as an example of why such
weapons wouldn\'t be used. I point to the same attack as an example of
how effective treaties about such things are when the chips are down. 

The *only* thing preventing me from doing you in this way is the fear
that you might do *me* in.

BTW, if anybody bothers to work out the costs of the massdriver and
base in CT. MT and even TNE, go ahead and post them. 

