    'body' => 'Charles Collin in reply to Tom Trelenberg\'s "Unstreamlined ships" question,
said:
>But in Traveller, ships have contra-grav, so they should be able to lower 
>themselves slowly into the atmosphere no matter what their shape, and 
>they need not have high speed to keep them from crashing.  After 
>all, if a bunch of Vacc-suited guys in an open-topped air-raft can do it, 
>why can\'t a ship with contra-grav?

I am a sad traditionalist. The first time in CT I realised how much the grav
pods cost just to lift one air-raft, I immediately concluded that full
contra-grav for a ship would be prohibitively expensive. A few old designs
intended to be really flashy yachts (e.g. the Lone Dragon from an old White
Dwarf scenario) increased their costs and had anti-grav units specifically
allocated to the job of in-gravity maneouvre. The manouevre drive itself I
have play ala Starship Op\'s Manual, i.e. it can only redirect a small amount
of its thrust off the main ship\'s axis - i.e. you have to be streamlined and
glide in, or come straight down on your tail. Only in the latter case can
you have any chance of \'hovering\' down slowly if un-streamlined, unless you
have 6G drives, in which case the % of G you can direct off-axis might be
enough to counter an Earth-type world\'s 1G gravity. (shouldn\'t G be g
anyway?). If we assume hovering in a dispersed structure on its tail is a
pretty risky thing ("Hey, watch out for that gust of wind..." - is everyone
assuming nice sunny days or can these planets be like the nasty storm-swept
one in Alien?) then we must consider landing. If a non-streamlined ship
isn\'t designed to land then it won\'t have anything other than emergency
landing gear (no manufacturer will put on unnecessary extras like that if it
means his ship will cost more than a competitor). Then there are dispersed
structures or even planetoids. Not normally nice flat evenly spread things
to try to land on a non-flat planet (or even at a nice flat starport). "This
is cap\'n Humbug of the planetoid Bull, to all ship\'s personnel. We have
landed safely... errrr... but we seem to be rolling down-hill..."

That\'s just how I\'d play it. If you don\'t like, don\'t use...

Cmdr Lilly, PITS (Political Intelligence Team, Scout)
PITS Team motto: "We are never outgunned."

