    'topic' => ' Size vs. Range',
    'body' => 'In <Pine.SUN.3.91.951025173456.15083F-100000@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> writes:
>A ship which is larger WILL tend to have a larger exhaust due to its (on
>average) larger powerplant (I assume you mean heat exhaust or drive
>exhaust).  Also, if you are detecting it by its albedo (I presume you mean
>energy bouncing off the ship?), then a larger ship will give off a more
>powerful signal due to its larger profile.  For instance, if the profile 
>of a ship facing your sensor is 100 m^2 and each m^2 is putting out 1 
>unit of energy, then a larger ship with a profile of 10000 m^2 will put 
>out 100 times the absolute amount of energy.

A larger ship will have a correspondingly larger power plant only if the 
designers of the ship feel that it is important to have the same performance
as the smaller version.  My point was that exhaust size is a function of the
sizes of the maneuver drive and power plant and not of the ship itself.

The albedo (amount of energy reflected from a ship) of a ship is also not
dependent upon the size of the ship but on the materials from which the EM
radiation is bouncing off.  While it is true that given two civilian ships, 
one being 100 tonnes and another being 1000 tonnes, the former will generally
have a lower albedo than the latter, this is not a hard and fast rule.  A 
1000 ton pirate ship, equipped with special radar-absorbing paint, may well 
have a albedo much lower than a 100 ton scout/courier.

Maybe I\'m just nitpicking, but I wanted to make clear that the visibility of
a ship\'s exhaust and the albedo of a ship are not really related to size, it 
just works out that way most of the time.

In fact, I see an adventure possibility here.  The naive merchant captain 
identifies the ship (not having Sensor Ops skill) has being between 100 and 
200 tonnes based on the albedo and the drive exhaust.  Of course, the 10,000 
ton camouflage-painted Zhodani warship tricked the captain by powering down 
the exhaust ...

-- 
