    'topic' => 'More on Size vs. Range',
    'body' => 'In x422, Steve Charlton wrote the following: 

______
Its not going to be as simple as all of that.  The albedo is influenced by
size, but a far more important element (in terms of detection) would be
material and finish.
______

I agree, I was assuming that those factors would be held constant, seeing 
as all ships in Traveller are said to be made out of "hull metal", 
whatever that is.  Also, nowhere in any of the design rules (book 2, High 
Guard)  does it have any mention of differing hull materials.  These 
would presumably cost different amounts, and no price diffs are given 
between military and civilian ship hulls.  I does make sense, though, 
that military ships would have "stealth" coatings of some sort. Still, 
for a given hull material/finish, a larger ship will be easier to 
detect. 

Also, if you are making initial detection based on neutrinoes emited
from the powerplant, then the ship\'s detectability would be entirely 
dependent on its plant output/size, which does tend to rise with the 
ship\'s size.  Your assertion that military ships would be better 
maintained and "less leaky" would make sense if you could shield-in 
neutrinoes, but you can\'t.  A neutrino can pass through something like 4 
light-years of lead on average before interacting with a single atom.  
Nothing you put around the drive could reduce their output rate.

And, as you pointed out, there are definately examples of military craft 
with huge signatures, even when size is factored out.  

Charles Collin.

