    'index' => 'ab926',
    'topic' => ' XBOAT digest 423',
    'body' => 'Hi all,

There have been a few questions asked Re: lasers  
that haven\'t yet been answered, so here is my contribution.
I hope it helps.

	Re: Lasers; Any beam of light will diverge from a perfect 
line by an angle given approximately by:

Theta = 1.2 L/d

where Theta is in radians, L is the wavelength of the light, and 
d is the diameter of the focal array. 
eg. for a 1-meter array and 10^-7 m light ( 1000 Angstroms, EUV)

Theta = 1.2 * 10^-7

This angle is useful for the following reason: the spot size on the target
will be (again approximately, since I\'m using the small-angle approx.
sin(x) ~ x for small x )

S = Theta * D ,  where D is distance to target.

THe area of the spot is then Pi * S^2

Conservation of energy implies that the energy flux put into the beam 
be spread over the spot area. Thus 

I = E * d^2 / ( 4 * L^2 * D^2 ), where  I is intensity in Mj per square
meter, E is input Mj, and d, L and D are all in metres.

At least this is what I\'m thinking right now. Mind you, it\'s rather
late and my brain is quite fried, so there might be a few mistakes in there..

However, the important point to remember is that a laser weakens at 
large distances above all by being spread out. A while back someone 
claimed a laser would be "a pencil-thin beam too weak to do any damage"..
not so....it gets bigger with distance, not smaller.
 
There has been some talk about laser combat at ranges around 10
light-seconds. Keep in mind that for the above mentioned EUV laser
at that range the spot diameter will be on the order of 300 meters.
=> energy per square meter is (input energy / Pi* 90,000). In TTNE they 
talk about 150 Mj lasers. that kind of input energy will result in a
few kilojoules per square meter. Thus grav focussing. At that point, 
you\'ve pretty much thrown physics out the window. Which is sort of 
a point of the game... However, the easiest way to compromise is to 
say that Grav focussing  changes the apparent aperture diameter. 

What\'s really cool is that you can apply these same formulas to a 
beam of neutral particles such as neutrons, using L = h*c/E where
E is the energy per particle, c the speed of light and h is Plancks Constant.
Be that as it may, the result is that L is many orders of magnitude
smaller for Neutrons -> thus a neutron beam will not diverge as quickly
as a laser beam. which is why you would expect an NPAW to be a long-range 
weapon. 

Final point: I vaguely recall someone claiming that mesons actually
could penetrate matter without resistance. I\'m afraid that is 
simply not true. The might not scatter off of electrons, but they do 
scatter off of nuclei.  Thus you have to sort of cough discreetly
and wave your hands when you\'re explaining how a meson gun works.
But that doesn\'t mean they\'re not cool, and this IS a scifi game, right?

Cheers,
/ben

     

