    'topic' => 'size vs. range and camouflage',
    'body' => 'Erwin Fritz\'s comments on radar- (etc.-) absorbing paint
(and presumably other surface coverings) leads me to ask
about how others on the list paint their naval and other
military spaceship miniatures. 

I always paint them flat black, assuming that that would be 
the best all-around camouflage in space.  It would reflect 
virtually no light and therefore be hardest to see.  I 
assume that the radar-absorbent camouflage doesn\'t have to 
be any particular color, and is therefore black, too.  

To develop some visual interest, I usually put on some
small insignia and pick out some details.

Is my concern with visual observation unnecessary in light 
of Traveller\'s far future sensors?  Even if visual contact 
isn\'t normally part of space combat, I would want to have 
every possible advantage, and would still go with flat 
black.

Civilian and other non-military ships of course reflect
their owner\'s desires (often in the form of corporate or
governmental policy, and are usually brightly colored to
facilitate rescue and general rendezvous activities. They
may also use radar-reflective paint (or alloy tiles or
whatever) to make themselves easier to see. 

