    'index' => 'ab930',
    'topic' => ' Gravitics',
    'body' => '>Reply-To: xboat@MPGN.COM
>
>Okay, I\'ve got a problem here which may stir up some debate:  How do grav
>plates work?  Obviously, there can be no answer of a purely scientific
>nature, but it\'s nice to have a fictional operating principle for
>technobabbling purposes.
>
>Here\'s my major concern:  Why do grav plates not exert their forces on
>other bodies outside the ship?  For instance, if you turn on a 1G floor
>field, then why does it not pull on the planet below you with a force of
>1G?  If you\'re using a 6G field to compensate for an average fighter\'s
>acceleration, you should throw whole solar systems into disarray!
>
>So, what do you think?
>

My simple eplanations (not overly detailed) is that gravitics break down
into two fields: anti-grav and artificial grav.

Antigravs generate thrust. They do this by acting upon the existing gravity
well, and the energy of the system is maintained. Basically they use the
gravity well as a lever, and use the energy of the bodies in the system as
their reaction mass.

Artificial gravity I treat as a field existing between two plates, by flow
of pseudo-gravitons.

Neither of these match any cannonical sources I have found, but work well
in play. Note that my theory of Anti-grav and thruster plates prevents
using T-plates for interstellar travel... the gravity wells are strong
enough to push against.


