    'index' => 'ab935',
    'topic' => ' MD planet busters.',
    'body' => 'Hi all,
	I felt it was time to add something to the MD debate..

While it\'s a nice idea, it\'s not quite such a sure-fire thing as 
you might like, for several reasons;
a) physics. A 1-ton projectile travelling at 1.5% c has roughly 
10^23 ergs of kinetic energy. this is a lot (500 Megatons is 
reasonable)  and is roughly enough energy to vaporise about a 
million tons of water or dirt, etc. This would certainly
ruin your day if you got in the way -but it would NOT significantly
damage a planets biosphere, nor destroy "everyone on the side of the 
planet"
Bad news for a starport or other base  o even a city - not a planet buster.

Also, keep in mind that while we might not be able to do much 
about a rock of that kind today - a TL-15 world probably would.
after all, anti-ship missles are quite small and equally stealthed,yet 
point defence systems can deal with them. a 1.5%c rock would 
probably be detected - if for no other reason than that any EM radiation 
bounced off of it would be quite noticeably doppler-shifted. 
Once detected it can be dealt with by military forces. (more on that in a moment)
You talk about angular resolution. well, there is such a thing as interferometry. already there is semi-serious talk among astronomers of optical 
interferometers with orbital baselines. in the radio we already have VLBI.
the angular resolution you can get is quite amazing. 
I would be very disappointed if they didn\'t have stuff better than that 
at TL-15. Numbers? well, the angle subtended by a 1km rock at 100 AU is 
about 6*10^-11 radians. To resolve this with 5000 Angstrom visible light
 you need 
a baseline of 7500 meters. That\'s not really that bad....


Another point - you talk about mid-course corrections. You will need rather 
powerful thrusters to make a noticeable change in course, because of your 
high velocity. THose thrusters will be seen. they will also require power. 
are you going to put a power plant on your rock - or just solid bossters. ?
and if you do, then it\'s not a rock, it\'s a missile or guided bomb. which makes
knocking it out easier - you don\'t need to deflect it or vaporize it - just 
fry its guidance and it will miss. that is easy with a laser or five.

No, the best apprach is to launch an unguided rock with high precision. which 
unfortunately means that you have to be rather close by. 

And by the way - how do you want to get you 1 million gee accelleration? 
THat\'s a pretty powerful accellerator.. how are you going to power it.?
batteries? You can\'t use fusion, you know, or you will be seen.

this brings us to the second major area of objection;

logistics. So, you want to spend several months or years building this MD 
deep inside a 1km iceball in the Oort cloud of one system. Cool. that means
you have to figure out how to set up a virtual construction site with ships 
coming and going... you\'ve red the debate about jump flashes. I will leave that be since it has already been discussed to death. 
But not only that, your MD will not be very moveable. fine, you can hit any
base in one system. but if that system doesn\'t happen to be a depot, what 
have you won?. the enemy will start to get a clue once ner lightspeed rocks 
start flying out of the void and zapping their bases. 
  
To summarize; if you\'re willing to spend more money building this thing 
than the enemy is in keeping a watchful eye (with sensor drones no doubt),
AND if you won\'t need to move the asset, AND if you merely want to vaporize 
a few bases, THEN fine, go for it. 

I\'d rahter spend the money on a few Tigresses, so i could defend 
my home base, and then jump  in one fine day and nuke the planet - using 
screens, point defence lasers, and armor to survive until I was close enogh 
for a few nukes to do the job. 

cheers,
/ben
















