    'year' => 1995,
    'from' => 'Charles Collin charles@hebb.psych.mcgill',
    'body' => 'Leonard Erickson writes:

> No you can\'t. Sensors have a limit known as "angular resolution". That
> means that they can\'t resolve things that subtend less than their
> angular resolution. The higher the angular resolution, the *wider* the
> sensor array has tto be, abd thus the hard it is to turn.

I realize that.  If you put a few satellites around your planet in an 
orbit a million kms out, you can easily and affordably get an array 2 
million kms wide.  If that\'s not enough, you can put them 10 million kms 
apart.  Whatever it takes.


> For refeuling and observation, all you need is a body in the 1 km
> range. 1 AU is 150e6 km. So 100 is 1.5e9 km. What\'s arctan 1/1.5e9?
> Answer, a *very* small angle.

But you don\'t have to detect the body, just all the neutrinoes coming off 
your power source (assuming it\'s nuclear).  

> Again, you are wrong. If I do the melting on the "back" side of the
> body, they won\'t be able to *see* the "heat" because it\'ll all be
> radiating in the wrong direction.

Maybe, but you\'d have to be careful not to let any hot gases leak.  Also, 
depending on how much heat you generate, it could radiate through a small 
body or show up in any traces of "atmosphere" it has (i.e. gases which 
have floated off and accumulated around the body, not gravitically held 
there, but orbiting with it).  And there\'s still the neutrino problem.  I 
think you would have a hard time.

> > Furthermore, if the Oort cloud is a good source of fuel, then it will 
> > definately be scanned for just this sort of activity.  
> 
> But how it is scanned, and from *where* make a big difference. And
> there is a distinct limit to how paranoid you can *afford* to be.

It doesn\'t cost much to put a few hundred or even a few thousand  
mass-produced sensor buoys all over the system (including the Oort cloud, 
if that\'s a consideration).  Besides, can you really put a price on peace 
of mind? :-)

> BTW, if your sensors are good enough to pick this sort of thing up at
> 100 AU, they\'ll get *fried* by the incredibly stronger signals from
> things like other planets in the system, and ships manuevering.

The sensors won\'t get fried.  You simply adjust their sensitivity to 
whatever level of signal you\'re looking at.  The human eye does this, and 
can thus handle signals varying along 14 log units in intensity.  You 
think a mechanical sensor can\'t be built to handle the same thing?

> This is one of the *major* limits on astronomy right now. There\'s too
> much background noise.

Any level of background noise can be factored out as a known constant.  
Again, the human eye can do it, why can\'t a machine?

> But they have to balance the assumed likelihood of it happening vs the
> costs of protecting against it.

They would also factor in what\'s at stake.  As I mentioned, the cost of 
putting a LOT of sensor buoys all over the place is small.  And this 
network would provide very powerful detection abilities by coordinating 
signals and triangulating.

> We know damn well that a medium sized asteroid could wipe us out, but
> we are only making half-hearted efforts to do anything about it.

Personally, I think the reason we are not doing much about it is that 
laypeople just don\'t buy it.

> But I\'m *not* sending an asteroid. I\'m sending a dinky little 1 ton
> chunk of nickel iron, well stealthed, and equipped with manuevering
> jets to make midcourse corrections. Less than half a meter across.

Ah, it has jets on it.  I must have missed that in your last post.  That 
changes alot.  I was thinking something which was coming in on an 
unchangeing vector.  No matter how small an object is, if it is ballistic 
then it should be trivial to eliminate it.

> And what are the odds of them being able to hit a target that small at
> several light seconds? Answer, just about nil.

I disagree.  They could cover a huge area with overlapping fire, making a 
"beaten zone" through which the asteroid has to come to reach the planet.  The 
asteroid could thus be vaporized.  At the speed it\'s going, no matter 
what size thrusters you put on it, it\'s not going to be able to change 
course that much, so it will have to come through a predictable area.

> The course *won\'t* change. Physics doesn\'t work that way. The pieces
> will start spreading, but they should all hit a target the size of a
> planet. And "vaporising in the atmosphere" sound great. But it isn\'t.
> The *full* impact energy will go into the planet\'s atmosphere *if* the
> pieces vaporise. That could ruin the planet right there.

Depending on the distance you hit them at, they may in fact miss the 
planet.  Also, any peices which hit the atmosphere at a low enough angle 
will "skip off".  Even if this is a consideration, all it means is you do 
have to vaporize the asteroid, which you can do.

> patterns. It\'s also not certain that pieces travelling at 1.5% of c
> will have *time* to vaporise.

Hmm, that\'s an interesting point.  I don\'t know.

> On a vacuum world, you\'d have to dig one *hell* of a long way to be
> same. Tens to hundreds of kilometers. And again, the radiation (X-rays
> and gammas) from the plasma cloud would be lethal for hundreds or
> thousands of km. You *don\'t* harden gear against *that* level of
> radiation.

I dont\' think 10 kms down is excessive.
If you\'re putting in 500 Megatons, you\'re basically hitting them with a 
medium-level nuclear bombardment.  Of course you\'d do damage, but you 
won\'t crack the planet open.  Anyway, I don\'t think it\'s that difficult 
to vaporize the thing.  If you bust it up into small enough bits, the 
impact will be spread out enough that its not a biggie.

> Not as difficult as you may think. :-)

Yes, as difficult as I think!  :-)  You\'d never be able to get the thing 
built before you were discovered anyway!


Charles Collin.
