    'index' => 'ab949',
    'topic' => 'Sensors -detection & resolution',
    'body' => 'Hi there

re. Detection and sensors

Glenn M. Goffin asked if his concern about visual appearence was
irrelevant in light of Traveler\'s advanced sensors.  I don\'t think so.
The visual and near-visual range band is the best understood in terms
of instruments to observe, and will probably remain so.  In addition,
on planets with Terran-like atmospheres, the visual range (along with
radio) will still be the most useful, so for flexible sensors you can
use for orbital survys or on-world, you need to consoder optical
sensors, and so you need to consider visual camo.  There is no point
in making your vessel radar absorbant, reducing your powerplant and
heat emission as much as possible, and taking various other steps to
reduce visibility to high-tech sensors if you then paint your vessel
bright orange with green polka dots and add a neon sign saying "we are
here"!  Of course, camo technology keeps up with sensor technology,
and you get chameleon circuits (which can work at visual wavelengths
as easily as IR/heat wavelengths, as far as I can see) and
looking-glass circuits.

Someone pointed out that to scan your sytem contents you only need to
consider two dimensions, ie. the sky area, and not the third
dimension, ie. distance from the observer.  Someone else said that you
*did* need to consider distance, as the further away an object is the
smaller it appears, and the harder it is to resolve.  However, if you
are just trying to *detect* an object, you do not need to resolve it.
You just look at your bit of sky, and wait for the characterisitic of
"jump emergence" or "melting ice" to appear.  The distance element
does come in, because what you are looking for appears dimmer the
further away it is; thus you need to look for longer (integrate) to
see further.  If you pick your required distance coverage, you can
determine how long you need to look for in each direction.  Resolution
is still important, but not fundamental.  The greater your resolution,
the more accurate the position you find, so the smaller the volume of
space which contains the observed object.  However, if this is out in
the Oort cloud, knowing something is there is more important than
knowing exactly where it is.  Also, the higher the resolution, the
smaller your field of view, so that you can only see a smaller bit of
sky at a given time.  This means you either need to move your sensor
more often, or build more sensors.  I guess a compromise between cost,
complexity, and effectiveness would be to have numerous "detection"
sensors of low resolution, and a few "lock-on" sensors to follow-up
the detections.  Resolution is also important in verifying identities,
and providing early warning of movement, etc.


This stuff about resolution brings us back to the use of visual
sensor/camo in combat.  As the resolution of a sensor is the operating
wavelength divided by the sensor aperture/array diamter (l/d), the
resolution which a 1 metre optical telescope can get at visual
wavelengths is as good as that of a 100 km radio telescope! On Terra,
in the atmosphere, optical telescopes are restricted to much worse
than this (the diffraction limit), but the Hubble Space Telescope is
very small compared with the major ground-based telescopes; its
location in orbit makes all the difference.  Thus, optical telescopes
and interferometers on a starship will be very important resolving
devices, which in turn is important for placing your targets
accurately.

