    'id' => '<Pine.SOL.3.91.951030102035.623C-100000@osiris>',
    'index' => 'ab950',
    'body' => 'Hi there

There has been some debate re. the inverse square law.  Here is my Cr
0.02 worth.

EM radiation (light, etc.) from a spherical-wave source (which may be
spherically symmetric, eg. a star, or just part of a sphere, eg. a
spotlamp bulb) will diminish in intensity as the square of the
distance from the source, because the photons or wave-front are
diluted across the surface of a sphere, the area of which increases as
the square of the distance. This is why gravity also follows the
inverse square law, because the gravitons (or whatever the current way
of think is) are diluted across a surface. 

Laser light is not as affected by the inverse square law, as they
produce narrow beams of coherent light, effectively flat wave fronts,
so the photons do not dilute.  Actually, this has more to do with the
way we make lasers work, than the laser mechanism itself.  In radio
astronomy, we see astronomical masers (like lasers, but with
microwaves), which emit in all direction, although we can only see
them from one direction (because that is where we are!).  There is a
sort of inverse square law for lasers, due to diffraction.  Any laser
has an aperture, where the light escapes.  For light of wavelength l,
and an aperture diamter d, diffraction causes the beam to spread at an
angle roughly l/d (radians).  This means that the area of the laser
spot increases as rl/d squared, at a distance r.  Thus the energy
density of the beam decreases at the inverse of this, ie d/rl squared,
giving an inverse square law which depends on the diameter of the
laser and the wavelength it operates at.  The laser intensity is
greater at a given range than that of normal radiation for two
reasons: (i) by fiddling with d and l you can attempt to optimise d/l,
and (ii) lasers are able to get a musch greater intensity at source
for the same energy input.  Thus, lasers have a greater range than a
big heat lamp.

