    'day' => '31',
    'index' => 'ab960',
    'topic' => ' Unstreamlined Ship Landings',
    'body' => 'Someone let me have it for saying that missiles would knock a ship around 
at 10 g\'s.  Sorry, that was a bit of hyperbole.  Let me put it another 
way: a ship that can stand the rigors of combat (e.g. shock waves from 
nuclear weapons, high-g maneuvers) should be able to support its own 
weight when landing.  Now before someone tells me about naval battleships 
trying to stay together on land or something, let me remind everyone that 
the original question was about a PC ship (i.e., less than 1000 tons I\'m 
guessing).  It\'s strength-to-mass ratio should be pretty good.

About water landings.  Its true that the ship might flip over, but the 
characters would still be able to get out intact (though maybe very 
wet).  And the original question was (if I recall correctly, which 
certainly isn\'t guaranteed) about a desperation maneuver of sorts.

The other thing is, the ship could hover on its grav thrusters and drop 
people off.  Someone 
said that equipping a ship so it could act like an air-raft would be 
expensive, but I\'m thinking the ship already has all sorts of grav plates 
and inertial compensators in the bulkheads.  How much more could it cost 
to put some on the bottom?  I\'ve always assumed that Traveller ships have 
three means of getting around:  grav for taking off gently and getting 
around in atmosphere, thrusters for space travel, and jump for interstellar.

Weather conditions should not be a problem either.  The ship can send 
small amounts of thrust in various directions to keep it stable.  
Otherwise, how do these ships survive to skim from gas giants?  There are 
some pretty powerful winds in there!

So, IMNSHO, there is no problem with unstreamlined ships landing, it just 
takes a lot longer and is against convention/safety rules (the Imperial 
version of the FAA would get all over you).  

Charles.

