----
I think it might be an interesting twist to work as a fraction of the max 
JDrive output. (i.e. \'The enemy ship is jumping at half power sir\'... you 
dont know if that is J1 from a J2 drive, or J3 from a J6 drive, unless 
you know the type of ship.)
----
>However, actually predicting the destination requires (i) high 
resolution imaging of the hull grid at jump and (ii) large amount of 
computer time.  Even then, it would be almost impossible without at least 
two points of view (otherwise, how do you know what is happening to the 
grid on the other 
side of the vessel?), and a good idea of the operating parameters of the 
jumping vessel.
----
And this assumes you know the jump grid pattern. You\'d be stuffed if you 
were trying to reverse-engineer the hull-grid energising pattern from an 
Aslan ship without an Aslan navigation computer to work back from. 
Preferably for that style of hull-grid, too.

The first mention of Jump \'Flare\' is in the SOM. I think that it is 
intended to be entirely \'chrome\'. Also there is nothing to indicate that 
the emissions carry for any distance. They may break down quickly, only 
for a short distance appearing as EMS in the visible light region.

It may be possible to write software that would handle the 
reverse-engineering process. I suspect it would be a major project. Given 
that the SOM declared that the grid had to be charged in the correct 
sequence to the *millisecond* I doubt that anything other than a cpu feed 
from the departing ship would be adequate.

I wonder if one could assume that other heavy earth alloys produce 
different colors/spectra or lower magnitude bursts?

A P Madden


