  {
    'index' => 'ab974',
    'body' => 'Hi. A few replies to various people:

Observing Base in Oort Cloud:
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Okay! Okay!  I\'m willing to believe it could be done.  But there\'s still 
the problem of getting the ship there without its jump flare being 
detected (see my previous post in this issue).  Also, if the ship is 
running on fusion, it\'s still going to have that nasty neutrino 
signature.  Granted, you probably won\'t be picked up right away from 
this, but you\'d better be ready to split real fast in case you are.  

The fact that we don\'t know anything about our Oort cloud in the 20th
century has little to do with it.  Before WWII, we had little knowledge of
what lay in deep coastal waters, but now we watch them quite carefully,
because we know an enemy could put a sub out there and listen in.  

Also, you have to remember that the Spinward Marches is a sector that has 
been through no less than FIVE wars by 1111, and much more conflict as 
you go further forward in its history.  I submit that there would be 
loads of anti-espionage equipment and procedures all over the place.


Common sense in Gunnery:
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
I was not trying to imply that common sense would mathematically narrow 
down the area in which a ship could be, but a gunner who had a limited 
number of shots to put out there would be more likely to assume (for 
example) that a fleeing ship would be in certain areas of the probability 
bubble and concentrate his fire there.  People do use unorthodox 
tactics, but not very often (or they wouldn\'t be unorthodox would they?  ;)


Nanites and Von Neuman Machines:
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Thanks for the info and comments!


Jump Emergence Flares:
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
I think I over-estimated the brightness of jump flares.  The 10^9 figure 
is the level at which damage occurs to vision.  In order for the flare to 
be painfully bright, it could be as low as 10^7 cd/m^2.

Charles


