> > Any non-maneuvering target that can be detected can be hit at those
> > tech levels.
>
>No it can\'t. As noted above, you reach a point were your CEP (circular
>error probable) is so much bigger than the target, that hits are
>essentially impossible.
>

Any non-maneuving target that can be tracked can be hit with a missile of
sufficient endurace. See last week\'s "Nova" for the current problems with
detection.

> > TL-15 isn\'t just 20th century tech with jump-drives shoved in it,
> > computer and sensor tech will have improved (very conservatively) a
> > thousand-fold!
>
>Sensor tech *cannot* improve that far. There\'s not a thousand-fold
>increase in sensitivity *left* to make. Once you can detect down to the
>level of the background noise, you *can\'t* get any improvement in
>detection by increasing the sensitivity. We already have sensors that
>can register individual photons at most wavelengths. You *can\'t* do
>better than that.
>
>The problem is seperating the signal from the backround noise. And
>other than reducing the noise generated *in* the sensor, you can\'t do
>anything about noise. It is not *possible* to detect any signal weaker
>than background noise. Period. If you think otherwise, you do not
>understand the subject.
>
>Improvements in computer tech aren\'t relevant here.
>
Were that entirely so, we\'d know nothing about the corona. The problem with
dim objects isn\'t wheter or not the background is greater apparent
magnitude, but the ability ability to notice changes from background that
are orders of magnitude smaller than background, and in the same
frequencies as background. Computer tech can improve effective sensor
performance significantly, by allowing greater discrimination. The problem
with current low light sensors is that their sensitivity is only within a
low magnitude; the future is in sensors which have an operational
flexibility at great magnitudes, while still being able to discriminate
fluctuations of a tiny magnitude.

>You missed my point *totally*. I did not say that you couldn\'t see a
>candle at 100 feet. I said that you couldn\'t see one at 100 feet if I
>was shing a *brighter* light into your eyes from 10 feet away! That\'s a
>*considerably* different situation, and it demonstrates the "background
>noise" problem. Heck, light a candle outdoors on a sunny day. Then
>*try* seeing the flame from 100 feet away on a bright, sunny day. You
>aren\'t likely to be able to see it unless there\'s a dark background.
>The ambient light levels overwhelm it.
>
> > In fact, under ideal conditions, you can see a candle flame up to 1
> > km away!  But that doesn\'t matter, my point is that if a messy
> > biological system like the eye can adjust to light levels ranging
> > from 10^-6 cd/m^2 to 10^10 cd/m^2 and still see detail, then TL 15
> > sensors should be able to do much better.
>
>And my point is that the sensor is going to be limited by the
>*brightest* source in it\'s fields of view, as well as by background
>noise. A ship at 1 light second will totally overwhelm any signals from
>100 AU.
>

Again, look at coroagraphs: effectively looking at a candleflame right
round an arclight. By carefull notation, and useing very sensitive
materials with a high base magnitude, we can see the corona in some types
of solar imaging WITHOUT occluding the solar disk. Or we can occlude the
solar disk. It\'s all a mater of knowing 3 things:

        1) how to build a sensor with a wide enopugh range to deal with the
background magnitude
        2) How to make said sensor accurate within a VERY small magnitude
from the base magnitude
        3) how to interpret the tiny variations in said magnitude (or
setting the squelch right) so as to detect those variations.

       At that point, the limitation becomes not the background magnitude,
but how much the background varies.

I suspect that that\'s the TL 16-18 range limit: How much does background
VARY, not how strong it is.

By TL 15, the sensitivity should be pretty good. And yes, we can track
objects of under 10m out to several LS... NASA currently does to around
lunar orbit (over 1.5 LS). NASA and the USAF are actively tracking over
3000 objects in orbit, some under 0.25m. (Again, See "Nova", the recent one
about the threat of cometary Impact. {I thought fondly of this thread while
I wathced it})



