    'index' => 'ac035',
    'topic' => 'J-torps vs. Xboats',
    'body' => 'Charles Collins writes

>1) Why have an X-boat network for delivering mail?  Why not just have a 
>bunch of mass-produced little jump-6 torpedoes speeding all over the 
>universe?  They could even carry some types of very small cargoes.  And 
>they would be much cheaper.

The price of the torpedoes is not listed in Leviathan (not that I can
find). Their reliability is not mentioned either. I get the impression
that the lack of mention of reliability means that they are fairly
reliable. I would NOT imagine that they are cheap tho. (If you have to
ask how much, you probably can\'t afford it...) And they certainly cannot
carry as much information or cargo as an Xboat. And each one of them
would have to have a miniaturized model 4 computer and jump-4 drive. This
would run to what? MCr20? MCr40? I don\'t have my books here, so I don\'t
know how much the standard sized stuff is. I do not imagine that the
miniature models would be cheaper. And they would have to be to make the
Cr/megabyte cost of transport lower.

Given the fact that the Xboat network exists, I would guess either that
J-torps are very expensive, or that the Imperial Officials in charge of
the Xboat network are getting some serious kickbacks from the
contractors who build and maintain the network. Or both (and the two
explanations might be related.)

	Another explanation might be found by looking at the modern day
US. Why do we subsidize an expensive, high-maintainance Interstate Highway
System instead of a cheap, low-maintainance interstate rail system?
There are probably lots of reasons, both good and bad. I can think of a
few; and some of these reasons might still apply in the 57th century.

				-Rob
