    'from' => 'PICL115@FSPHY1.HEP.FSU.EDU',
    'body' => 'Hi there:

I would first like to thank everyone who put in input for the "jump
torpedo" question.  The idea that passenger carrying jump capable
vehicles must be at least 100 tons, while strictly instumentation
laden vehicles may be of even smaller size seems like a good one
to me (...perhaps smaller jump grids (< 100 tons) will not adaqutely
shield biological systems from jump space, but can easily protect
relatively durable electronic system).  Combine this with the idea
that many do not survive the trip through jump space and are therefore
not reliable as an xboat substitute and I think they (jump torps) have
been worked into Traveller without upsetting the balance too much.
They would be used strictly as emergency devices (however as tech. 
improves they might eventully replace xboats--(boo hiss...)  The pony
express didn\'t last forever).  Again thanks for the ideas.

Secondly, in Xboat 434 I asked Paul Colley if he would expound on his
post concerning a local EMP generator (Xboat 420).  I did not mean to 
restrict this question only to Paul.  If anyone else has anything on
this please share with the rest of us.

Finally, I wanted to add some possible fuel to the already terribly bloody
mass driver war we are currently experiencing.  Some quick (and possibly
incorrect) calculations indicate that in order for a _mostly_ ballistic
projectile to hit an Earth-sized planet at 100AU, the 1000km long accelerator
will have to be accurate to within 87/1000 of a second of arc (manuevering
of projectile not assumed) to the position of the planet 40 days in the 
future (is this position known w/o error?).  I assume thrusters on the 1000km
diameter oort body will have to move the accel to this percision and then
stabalize it within this degree of percision as well.  Also, at tech 15
will components of a guidance system be able to withstand a 1000g impulse and
still remain properly calibrated?  Be calm, I\'m not saying it isn\'t possible,
