    'topic' => ' XBOAT digest 439',
    'body' => 'I certainly don\'t want to paint myself as an "expert" on EMP devices.
I\'ll admit I don\'t understand the theory of how they work.

However, I think there are some clear errors in Leonard\'s exposition:

>Date: Tue, 14 Nov 95 18:00:13 PST
>From: shadow@ (Leonard Erickson)
>To: xboat@MPGN.COM
>Subject: EMP bombs, mass drivers
>
>PICL115@FSPHY1.HEP.FSU.EDU writes:
>
> > Secondly, in Xboat 434 I asked Paul Colley if he would expound on
> > his post concerning a local EMP generator (Xboat 420).  I did not
> > mean to restrict this question only to Paul.  If anyone else has
> > anything on this please share with the rest of us.
>
>The basic idea is that you dump a huge current pulse into a coil
>wrapped around a ferrite or steel core. This creates a *huge* spike in
>the magnetic field. It also tends to impose huge stresses on the coil.
>Left to itself the coils would either explode (the magnetic field
>imposes a *significant* pressure on the coil) or melt from the high
>current flow.

This contradicts my (admittedly imperfect) understanding of how these
things work.

First of all, it\'s damn hard to create a "*huge* spike in the magnetic
field".  First and foremost, the coil is an inductor that resists
changes in current.  Setting up a strong magnetic field takes time.
That\'s *why* you create the magnetic field, then manipulate the device
mechanically (how\'s that for a sanitized way of saying "blow the sucker
up"?  :-)).  It\'s easier to use explosives to suddenly change the
physical characteristics of the device than it is to suddenly change
the current.

The coils are under some stress, but it shouldn\'t be
excessive----looking at my physics textbook (Halliday & Resnick
"PHYSICS") the net force on the coils seems to be quite small in
comparison to the magnetic field strength.  On the other hand, the
wires are admittedly fragile.  This could be a concern for the failure
of the device, but not for it failing explosively.

And the force, such as it is, works to force the coils closer together,
not apart.  An explosion is unlikely.  If the device fails at this
stage, it would likely be by coils being forced together to the point
at which the insulation fails and shorts, changing the coil into a
linear conducting tube (and thus essentially eliminating the magnetic
field).

Melting is of course quite possible----That\'s why these things have to
be cryogenically cooled.  Superconductors remove the heat problem; or
even short of superconducting, cooling with liquid nitrogen would be a
real good idea (drops resistence, and thus heat generation,
considerably, and cools the coils to boot).

>But at the moment the current peaks, you set off explosive charges
>arranged so as to implode the coil. Since the field is "trapped" in the
>core, imploding it raises the field density even higher. It also
>amplifies an "uneven-ness" in the field. These inhomogenities, combined
>with the the *huge* field density create the EMP. 

This part sounds plausible.

>As I understand it, we can build a briefcase sized device that\'d
>clobber most electronics for as much as 100 yards. And since the blast
>is an implosion, there\'d be very little blast damage (the briefcase
>would probably contain most of it).

We can\'t create an "implosion".  To implode things, you surround them
with explosives which compress the interior----but viewed from outside
of the device, it\'s still just a explosion.

The blast is small because all it has to do is destroy/explode/implode
(whatever) the coil.  The goal of implosion does nothing to restrict
the collateral physical damage.

- Paul Colley
