    'topic' => 'Andor and Candory',
    'body' => 'Glenn M. Goffin writes:

>"Several individual Tigresses [500 kton dreadnaughts] have been deployed 
>among the worlds of the Five Sisters subsector to enforce the amber zone 
>blockade of Candory and Andor."
> 
> Supplement 9, Fighting Ships, at 38.
>
>The reference to "amber zone" I assume to be a proofreading error, but 
>what about a blockade requiring "several" of the "largest line-of-battle 
>vessel[s] currently in service with the Imperial Navy in the
>Spinward Marches"?  
 
>Is the Imperium trying to keep something from getting out of Andor and
>Candory, or trying to keep someone from getting in?  Or is it really 
>just a cover or excuse for building up Imperial forces on the opposite 
>side of the Sword Worlds? 

They can\'t be trying to keep something from getting out of A & C, since
the starports prove (at least to me) that the Droyne have star travel.
In my universe only Jump-1 star travel, which they use to keep contact
between the two worlds, but star travel nevertheless. A jump-1 starship
with sufficient tankage could reach 5 or 6 parsecs out before it had to
refuel, so letting the Droyne have _any_ jump ships means you can\'t
keep them confined.

Wait! That\'s not quite true. You _could_ inspect each ship as it leaves
either of the planets and make sure it only has fuel for a jump-1. But
then there\'s that Droyne free trader in "Merchant". No, I don\'t think
that can be the truth. As for a cover for building up strength on the
other side of the Sword Worlds: Why would they need any excuse for that?

I still think that A & C is interdicted in order to prevent off-world
scavengers from plundering Ancient sites. Either that or the Imperium is
trying to prevent Joe Q. Public from learning that _every_ Droyne has
psionic abilities (Oh! The Horror!!) 



