Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> said:

> Steve mentioned that you could effectively replace sand with water.  This
> brings up an interesting little question:  what is "sand" in the first
> place?  Is actually just rock dust?  I\'ve always thought it was some sort
> of reflective chaff-like material and that "sand" was just a
> colloquialism.

I\'ve always assumed that it was sand to break up and refract the laser beam. 
In space it would work better than \'chaff\' (which is designed to look like a 
target to an oncoming missile\'s radar anyway).

> In terms of the CT system taking up lots of room, I usually reduce the
> time scale as previously noted, but one thing I\'ve always dreamt of is
> doing the opposite: increasing the scale by a factor of 10!  Picture this: 

> you get a football field, some long peices of rope with markings every ten 

> cms, and every model spaceship you can find, then you go out and fight
> the mother of all Traveller space combats!

A friend and I once used the CT system (actually the Mayday! rules, but the 
differences are very minor as I recall) to run a participation game at a 
show. We had a table about 6\' by 3\', covered with a black cloth and we used 
coloured thread pinned to the board (we had a cork board under the cloth) 
and some scratchbuilt starship models. It looked very impressive and we had 
a lot of interest.

Kind Regards

Dave Elrick
