    'day' => '21',
    'body' => 'Hi All.

>From William F. Hostman (re: sandcasters):
>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
Yes, there is cannon. I don\'t remember exactly where, but it explains the
sand of sandcasters. Something about manufactured silicone based crystals,
doped with ferrous compounds at earlier TL\'s, held in place by magnetic or
tractor fields. The Screens roll is to swing the field into just the right
position.
<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<


Yikes, that\'s totally different from the image I had.  Based on High 
Guard, I always thought that you were just firing large clouds of the 
stuff between yourself and the enemy.  

Also from Will:
>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
As to water, it\'s a great idea, but it\'s definitly not going to be as
effective. I\'d halve the effects by system in use for water based.
As for natural sand, well, gravitic priciple sandcasters would be able to
handle it... magnetics probably wouldn\'t.
And remember, it\'s the largest legal shotgun. (also cannon from either MT
or CT, don\'t remember which. But my players seem to always be able to show
me on a moment\'s notice.)
<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<

Maybe you know something about this I don\'t, but why would water be less
effective?  It refracts light quite nicely.  Also, for you physics types: 
how effective would a cloud of sand be?  How dense would it have to be to
have a decent effect?  What mass of sand per shot are we talking about
here?  As for the giant shotgun concept, I love that idea.  I wonder if
you could load different sorts of things into it (NOW FOR SALE:  The
Universe\'s Biggest Rock Salt Shotgun!).  Other sadistic ideas welcome. 


>From David Elrick:
>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
I\'ve always assumed that it was sand to break up and refract the laser beam.
In space it would work better than \'chaff\' (which is designed to look 
like a target to an oncoming missile\'s radar anyway).
<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<

But isn\'t part of the sand\'s effect to screw up sensors?  Why would it 
have effects against missiles and energy weapons otherwise?  Is it 
supposed to destroy missiles by impact?  The relative velocity could be 
really high, so that seems plausible, I\'m just not sure what the canon is.
Also, I can\'t see how a cloud of sand would really affect energy weapons.

Also from David:
>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
A friend and I once used the CT system (actually the Mayday! rules, but the
differences are very minor as I recall) to run a participation game at a
show. We had a table about 6\' by 3\', covered with a black cloth and we used
coloured thread pinned to the board (we had a cork board under the cloth)
and some scratchbuilt starship models. It looked very impressive and we had
a lot of interest.
<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<

Sounds cool, but I think the Mayday! rules must be somewhat different than
CT if you could run a large battle on a 6\'x 3\' table.  In CT, a ship can
quickly build up a vector of a meter or more.  That is the problem I have 
with it.  

This is the movement system I use now, let me know what you think of it 
(be gentle):

Hexes are 10000 km, turns are 1000 s.  One g/turn accelerates a ship by
one hex per turn.  All ships start with an initial speed in hexes, and one
of 12 directions (the hex sides and vertices are used).  A
ship has two counters on the board:  One a picture/miniature of the ship,
the other a simple arrow for pointing at its direction of travel.  When a
ship moves, you do the following steps: 

1. Initial Vector:  Leave behind the vector counter as a marker of initial
position and move the ship counter forward a number of hexes equal to its
present speed (in whatever direction it is presently moving). 

2. Thrust Vector:  Move the ship counter from its new location in any 
direction.  The maximum number of hexes moved equals the ship\'s thrust. 

3. Calc New Vector:  Count the number of hexes between the ship counter and 
its vector counter (which was left behind).  This is the ship\'s new 
speed.  The new direction is figured by tracing a line between the vector 
counter and the ship counter and "rounding" to one of the 12 directions.

4. Mark New Vector:  Now you record the new speed and move the vector
counter to the hex with the ship in it, pointing in the direction of
travel. 

I find this system quick, simple, and a good approximation of reality.  
If you want gravitational effects, they\'re easy to add in, but it helps 
if you change the time/size scale to 316 second turns on a 1000 km hex 
map so that you can have grav bands.  Unfortunately, this scale puts the 
ships really close to one another for firing purposes and you have to 
come with a justification for them missing one another.

I have one problem with my system and every other vector system I\'ve seen, 
though: 
Why does the ship appear at the head of its vector?  Shouldn\'t it be
halfway along the vector?  Delta-V is AT^2, but distance travelled is
half that, no?  This can have relevance in terms of range for firing, and 
gravitational effects.  


I can see the tomatoes flying already,

Charles.

