    'topic' => ' Sandcasters',
    'body' => 'Hi All.

	Regarding Energy Weapons:  According to the descriptions I\'ve
read, plasma and fusion weapons actually shoot out a blob (or stream or
whatever) of matter in a super-heated state.  Intuitively, I can\'t see a
cloud of sand having a significant effect on it.  One possibility is that
energy weapons are actually "plasers", meaning that the plasma \'rides\' a
laser to its destination.  This might be reasonable, since plasma would
otherwise scatter very quickly.  So, one could view sand as refracting the
guiding laser and thus causing the plasma to scatter. 

	To William F. Hostman:  Somebody asked for the source of the 
canon you provided a couple of issues ago regarding sand clouds that 
could be swung around by gravitics or magnetics.  I\'d like to second 
that motion :-)

	To Alvin Plummer:
> "Galatic empires will continue to arise and collapse in science fiction, 
> largely to satisfy a certain romantic need on the readers and writers."
>             - Lester del Rey, "The Visual Encyclopedia of Science Fiction"
> 
> Hmmm, can anyone expand on this?  Excuse my illiteracy, but 
> what does he mean by \'romanticism?\'  Dramatic? Historic? Idealistic?

I think del Rey means that SF fans want their future histories to be full
of big, decisive and clear cut events.  He is probably implying that these
sorts of events are unrealistic, but that they are none the less fun to
read about (and roleplay).  Some people even 
think the whole rise and
collapse idea in world history is innacurate and that historians have
latched onto it to make things seem more structured when they really are
not.  I\'ve had to defend the Long Night concept on several occasions
because my players considered it implausible for such a massive collapse
to occur (Safety Tip: Don\'t let ancient history buffs into your 
campaings!  :-).  I know some people on the T:TNE 
list do not buy Virus as a plausible cause of interstellar collapse. 

Oops, there I go, starting another contentious thread  :-)

Charles.

