Since you must (in anything extrapolatable from real scince) create
antimatter _ex nihilo_ so far as I know (e=mc squared in reverse...),
and no real world process can ever be 100% efficient, antimatter must
be considered to be an energy _storage_ system (like a battery) rather
than an energy source.  So, a "reasonable" return is not one which gives
more energy than it consumes, but one which allows you to retain enough
of the input energy to make the convenience (?) of using antimatter
worthwhile.

Now, if you are playing in the Spinward Marches, the Ancients apparently 
used a planet sized chunk of antimatter to bombard the plant which created
the Shionthy Belt in the Regina subsector, and loose chunks of it are still
floating around...energy storage, but over a rather longer period of time.
