X::>1. Why is antimatter such a difficult source of energy to develop (i.e.,
 ::>according to the Traveller background)?  We can produce very tiny amounts
 ::>of anti-matter now, and contain it.  It seems like a simple matter to
 ::>allow it to annihilate with normal matter and harness the energy.  Is it
 ::>simply a matter of producing sufficient quantities?

 Actually, it would be a matter (no pun intended) of _containing_
 the stuff - and that would be more important than being able to
 make it.  When I was about 8 years old, I thought that antimatter
 oxygen would only react with "promatter" (our stuff) oxygen; the
 book I was reading wasn\'t clear on that.  In reality, as you know,
 _any_ antimatter coming into contact with _any_ promatter will
 cause a nasty reaction.

 Now, you\'re going to carry this stuff around with you - how?  You
 can\'t build something out of promatter to attach your antimatter
 to; it will just cause a lot of pretty (and deadly) fireworks.
 You need fields that have all of the properties of matter except
 for the physicality - and they have to be not only airtight, but
 totally anything-tight; even a promatter neutrino coming into
 contact with your antimatter will cause a spark.

X::>2. Does producing antimatter use up more energy than it can potentially
 ::>return?  How likely is it that one could develop an efficient-enough
 ::>production technique to yeild reasonable returns (i.e., is this a 21st
 ::>century concept, or a 21st millenium concept?)?

 Conversion from promatter/antimatter to energy is one hundred
 (100.000000000) percent efficient.  Using totally unrealistic
 numbers, if the total annihilation of a single electron produces
 one joule of energy, then if it takes less than two joules of
 energy to create your antimatter electron _and_ capture into your
 fuel tanks you promatter electron, then you\'re ahead of the game.
 I\'d tend to think that it\'s probably not a XXIc concept, but
 should certainly be possible well before the CCXc.  Canon seems to
 imply that it\'s not possible in the LVIIc, but that it\'s not that
 many tech levels ahead.

X::>3. How likely is one to find large amounts of antimatter in
 ::>space?  If a system were made of anti-matter, would we know it?  Could
 ::>there be large amounts of "dark" antimatter out there?

 I\'d consider finding the stuff a doubtful proposition, regardless
 of the probabilities of its existence.  Antimatter has to exist
 pretty much in total isolation from promatter, otherwise you\'ll
 get reactions - and probably detectable ones, even with
 present-day technologies.  Some authors of speculative
 counterfactual literature have suggested the possibilities of the
 existence of entire antimatter galaxies, but the general consensus
 seems to be that they\'re not going to naturally coexist in the
 same galactic region.

X::>4. This one is a bit psycho:  If there were a collapsed anti-matter
 ::>object (black hole, neutron star, etc.), would it have different
 ::>qualities than the same sort of normal matter object?  What if a normal
 ::>matter black hole smacks into an antimatter black hole (do you get a
 ::>galaxy-cracking explosion, or just a more massive black hole?)?

X::>5. Aside from the particles having opposite charges, what are the
 ::>properties of antimatter?  Does it follow the same rules for gravity,
 ::>electromagnetism and so on?

 Our best information indicates that the electromagnetic and
 gravitic properties of antimatter and promatter are identical.
 The only difference seems to be in charge and spin.  The black
 hole question is a bit harder:  The definition of a black hole
 requires an escape velocity that is in excess of the speed of
 propagation of light \\in vacuo\\.  That implies that there would be
 no galaxy-cracking explosion when a promatter black hole and an
 antimatter black hole come together.  However, we usually discuss
 black holes in terms of mass density - and there would be no mass
 left afterwards.  It would all be converted to energy.  So where
 does the energy go?  The spectacular answer is that it goes
 nowhere until enough mass has been annihilated to bring the
 combined mass below the limit for a self-sustaining black hole,
 and then BLOOEY!  But, you still have the problem of where the
 energy goes _until_ the blooey point.

 More likely, IMO, is that where we talk of mass density for a
 black hole, or for any astrographic body, we should be talking
 about mass-energy density.  In which case, the total m-e density
 in the collision of a promatter hole and an antimatter hole would
 remain unchanged, and all you\'d get is a bigger hole.

