Not *exactly*, Jeff ...

Antimatter only reacts with matter particles of the same type: in other
words, an anti-neutrino will only react with the exact same type of
normal-matter neutrino.  Anti-electrons (positrons) react with electrons,
and anti-protons with protons, and so on.  Anti-protons aren\'t hard to make
(as antimatter goes), and are charged.  They *will* react with most objects
made of matter - because the nucleus of every atom contains protons.

Containing antimatter isn\'t quite as hard as you make out - *if* the
antimatter particles have a charge, they can be contained electromagnetically
just like any other type of subatomic particle.  You can use an airtight
containment vessel (made out of normal matter) to hold the vacuum, and inside
that have an electromagnetic container so that the antimatter doesn\'t escape
to hit the walls of the container.

Various clever designs have been developed for just this purpose; Dr. Robert
L. Forward mentions several that have been proposed in his book _Future
Magic_.  It\'s worth noting that current high-energy phsyics research centers
currently produce and store antimatter as part of their experimental
programs.  As a sweeping generalization, any technology that could contain
and maintain a fusion reaction for power generation could probably have no
trouble containing and controlling an antimatter reaction.

> X::>2. Does producing antimatter use up more energy than it can potentially
>  ::>return?

Yes.  Physics tells us that we cannot possible gain more energy from an
antimatter reaction than we used to create the antimatter.  The realities of
engineering are than nothing is 100% efficient, so producing antimatter will
require more energy than we could extract from an antimatter reaction.

On the other hand, antimatter does have the possibility of storing the most
energy in the smallest amount of "fuel" - you can\'t beat the energy density.
So at some point in the future, antimatter might be exploited as an energy
storage medium.

>  ::>How likely is it that one could develop an efficient-enough
>  ::>production technique to yeild reasonable returns

Dr. Robert L. Forward, in his book _Future Magic_ makes an argument to the
effect that for certain applications, antimatter could be a viable energy
storage medium for the forseeable (sometime in the 21st Century) future.

>  Conversion from promatter/antimatter to energy is one hundred
>  (100.000000000) percent efficient.

Several problems come to mind: depending on the antiparticles invloved, the
reaction emits a lot of it\'s energy in non-useful forms (such as neutrinos
or other difficult-to-capture particles).  In practice, the amount of useful
energy that\'s available for extraction from an antimatter reaction is (in
*really* round numbers) between 33% and 66%, depending mainly on the types
of particles involved in the reaction.  On top of that, you\'ll have to
factor in the losses by the energy-extraction mechanism, and any energy
required for containment of the reaction itself.

This is, however, a much more efficient reaction that fusion (which converts
about 0.1% of the mass involved into energy) and fission (about 0.01%).

> X::>3. How likely is one to find large amounts of antimatter in
>  ::>space?

If there were antimatter stars nearby, then some proportion of the primary
cosmic radiation would consist of antiparticles.  This hasn\'t been detected,
so we can assume that there are no nearby antimatter stars.  If there were
antimatter planets, nebulas, gas clouds, or other "dark" matter, the matter
in cosmic radiation (which pervades space) or solar wind (if there was a
nearby star) would react with the antimatter to produce all sorts of
interesting (and detectable) radiation.  Since no signs of these reactions
have been detected, it\'s been estimated that there are no significant
deposits of antimatter within our galaxy, and there are probably none in
nearby galaxies.

>  ::>If a system were made of anti-matter, would we know it?

Yes, from light-years away.

>  Could there be large amounts of "dark" antimatter out there?

Not in a galaxy with predominantly normal-matter stars.  They wouldn\'t be
dark, but would be lit up due to radiation from matter-antimatter reactions
with cosmic radiation and solar wind (as appropriate).

> X::>5. Aside from the particles having opposite charges, what are the
>  ::>properties of antimatter?  Does it follow the same rules for gravity,
>  ::>electromagnetism and so on?

Yes.

>  Our best information indicates that the electromagnetic and
>  gravitic properties of antimatter and promatter are identical.

The properties of antiparticles which we\'ve been able to produce (which
includes anti-electrons and anti-protons, and probably more by now) have
been pretty-well investigated, and found to be "as expected" (the reason it\'s
so well-checked is that *if* there was a difference, there\'d probably be a
Nobel prize in it for someone ...)

Too bad Metlay doesn\'t monitor this list; he could probably answer this
better than I could (and fix the errors that probably exist in the above).

Resident Traveller Dinosaur and Terrorist on the TML, wildstar@qrc.com

