    'topic' => ' More Antimatter Madness!!!',
    'body' => 'Well, I\'ve stirred up some interest with this one.  Thanks to everyone 
who replied.  Some of the information was a little contradictory, but 
very much appreciated nonetheless.  I would like some clarification on a 
couple of points:

1.  According to many, it is impossible to get more energy out of
antimatter than one puts into creating it.  I am of course familiar with
the laws of conservation.  But one can get more energy out of a log than
one puts into it by burning it.  This is because the log contains energy
which is released by a chemical reaction.  I guess my basic question is: 
why does it take so much energy to change the charge of a particle?  Why
does one have to put as much energy in as the mass of the whole thing,
isn\'t it just a matter of taking a mass and changing a property of it?  Or
do you have to "build" antimatter from energy?  (forgive my ignorance, I
let my subscription to "Exotic Particle Monthly" run out a year ago :-)

2. If one stores a bunch of anti-protons in a magnetic bottle, will there 
be a problem with free neutrons (i.e., radition) getting into the 
bottle?  Someone said that anti-particles will only react with the same 
sort of pro-particle, but others contradicted this.  Can I get a bit more 
input on this issue?  I realize that neutrinoes and such would not be a 
problem, as they would have low interaction probabilities anyway, and 
would only "use up" minute amounts of the antimatter anyway, but what 
about heavier particles?  You could sheild out any charged particles, so 
I\'m mainly worried about neutral ones.

3. If one allows anti-protons to react with normal protons, how much of 
the energy is released as waste neutrinoes and other "uncatchable" 
particles?  If I allow the whole mechanism of anti-matter plant to 
convert 10% of mass to useful energy is that unrealistic?  Fusion\'s .1% 
conversion, correct?  So this would be 100 times better.

Charles.

