    'from' => 'Roger Moore moore@hep.phy.cam.ac.uk',
    'body' => '> Okay, the antimatter thing seemed to interest people, so here\'s another 
> one for the physics types:  what the hell are mesons?  A while ago, 
> someone claimed that meson guns were "magic" in the sense that the mesons 
> do not actually go through matter.  

That was me :-)
Mesons are a combination of a quark and an anti-quark. Since there are 6 
types of quark and each pair can be combined in different angular 
momentum states this gives a lot of different mesons

> Why not?  

Because they interact with matter to produce showers of particles. The 
experiment I work on is essentially a large meson gun (type K :-) which 
produces two beams of Kaons (symbol K!). These decay to pions (another 
type of meson)

> How massive are they compared to say a neutron?  

Depends on the type. The lightest eg. pion, are about a tenth the mass of 
a neutron whereas the heavier ones discovered eg. B0 are about five times 
heavier than a neutron.

> If you moved them up close to C, couldn\'t 
> they penetrate quite a bit of matter? 

Yes, for example the fraction left after travelling a distance X through 
iron is:
	Fraction = exp(-X/0.176)      (X in metres)
(note that this is independent of the particle\'s energy)

but this is the same for protons and neutrons. Essentially any particle 
accelerator is as effective as a meson gun. The claims made in Traveller 
that they will \'sail through a planet and then decay\' are complete 
rubbish. Anything that did that would not be a meson.

> How much energy does a meson 
> release upon decay (or is this another bit of "magic")?  Wouldn\'t you 
> have to get huge numbers of them into the enemy ship to do significant 
> damage?

Depends on the meson. Generally the bigger the meson, the shorter the 
lifetime and the bigger the energy released. The energy will always be 
less than the mass of the particle and so will be insignificant compared 
to the energy you need to accelerate it to.

Roger
