    'from' => 'Massimo Stiavelli mstiavel@stsci.edu',
    'body' => 'Charles inquires further about anti-matter

I had refrained so far from entering the arena but will do so now..
(just to complement Roger Moore who, to be fair, covered much of the same )

1. antimatter is more than just a different charge. However this description
is not so far from truth for electrons and muons that are leptons ie light
and as far as we know elementary. Note that anti-neutrinos exist and are
different from neutrinos even though the neutrino has no charge. Anti-leptons
also have the lepton number reversed, not only the charge (by they way
there are also three brands of neutrinos commonly known as flavors).
For baryons, ie. protons and neutrons things are different since they are
composed particles. In high energy collisions between protons and antiprotons
often it is only a pair of quarks that anihilates leaving the remaining
four quarks do their business (which often means make mesons).
Indeed one makes antimatter out of energy, unless you have a magnetic
monopole and the laws of physics are about right to allow neutron-antineutron
catalysis (we do not know but looks unlikely).
On the other hand if you have mangetic monopoles either you are terribly
lucky or energy is not a problem for you..
Despite this if you could make anti-matter with more than 50 per cent
efficiency you would be well off since am would anihilate with ordinary
matter which you get for free.

2. magnetic containment is a tricky business but it can be done. The
problem is that of scale. At CERN they have been able to store something like
200 anti-protons for a couple of months..this is not what you would like..
Neutrons can be shielded relatively easily, getting a reall good vacuum
is more of a problem. Also one needs the antiproton beam to be really
cold, that is achievbed by the so-called stochastic cooling and also by
electron cooling if I am not mistaken. The trick is to cool it
down something you cannot touch (note that electrons can touch anti-protons
relatively safely). Perhaps Roger has more recent information on this.

3. I haven\'t any paper at hand to asnwer what is the typical fraction of
energy lost to neutrinos. I would not expect it to be large. However
even mesons (esp. the neutral ones) would be copiously produced and are then
you\'d need  a large shield to catch them before they escape with your energy.

Extra question. Mesons are particles made of two quarks, not to be confused
with muons that have no quarks since they are leptons.
Mesons can have quite a variety of masses, from 140 MeV (280 times 
the electron mass, but 1 seventh of the proton mass) to much heavier masses
when they include exotic quarks. The problem of the meson gun is not to
make it but to gain something out  of it. With just one particle it wouldn\'t
work since you would be releasing more energy in your ship (production 
efficiency of the mesons plus exponential decay) than in the opponent ship).
If you start using double decay meson guns, i.e. neutral mesons decaying into
charged mesons you could gain something. I doubt it would really work [but
it is fun to play!].

Since neutrons and protons are made of the same kinds of quarks (up and down)
anti protons can partially anihilate with neutrons.

Finally, on "natural" anti-matter sources. The astronomical upper limits on
anti-matter are quite tight. If there is any "nearby" it is probably so
far anyway that if you could reach it you wouldn\'t need it. This is
different for positrons. Even in our galaxy there is a source, known
as the Great Anihilator, that every now and then annihilates a few billions
tons of positrons in a nice flash that we can detected by observing gamma
emission peaked at 511 KeV. Standard models for pulsars and active
nuclei predict the existence of positron-electron atmospheres where the
number of e-p anihilating is compensated by the number freshly made by
hard radiation. instabilities are possible (ie the Compton catastrophe) and
one ends up with lots of gamma rays. I am not sure I would volunteer
to go and fetch them...

           Cheers,

                 Massimo
