<WARNING THE ANSWERS HERE ARE FROM A NON-PHYSICIST WHO DOESN\'T HAVE HIS 
BOOKS ON THIS TYPE OF STUFF WITH HIM>

Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> writes:

 ----
Okay, the antimatter thing seemed to interest people, so here\'s another
one for the physics types:  what the hell are mesons?
 ----

A sort of particle ;)

 ----
  A while ago,
someone claimed that meson guns were "magic" in the sense that the mesons
do not actually go through matter.  Why not?  How massive are they
compared to say a neutron?
 ----

At "rest" about a tenth or so of a Neutron.

 ----
  If you moved them up close to C, couldn\'t
they penetrate quite a bit of matter?  How much energy does a meson
release upon decay (or is this another bit of "magic")?  Wouldn\'t you
have to get huge numbers of them into the enemy ship to do significant
damage?
 ----

If you moved them that fast most of their energy would be in their movement, 
not their mass. They would penetrate until they hit a nucleus and did what 
ever it is that they do to Nuclei. They do release a significant amout of 
energy (it is a nuclear type decay thingy.. as in nukes) upon decay. You 
would need no more than a conventional particle beam.

One thing that annoys me about Meson Guns is the assumption that all the 
particles are going to decay at roughly the same distance. I thought that 
particles only had half-lives so mesons should decay from the muzzle 
onwards... with the intensity proportional to 1/(n^distance).

Roger Moore <moore@hep.phy.cam.ac.uk> writes:

 ----
> Antimatter only reacts with matter particles of the same type: in other
> words, an anti-neutrino will only react with the exact same type of
> normal-matter neutrino.  Anti-electrons (positrons) react with electrons,
> and anti-protons with protons, and so on.  Anti-protons aren\'t hard to 
make
> (as antimatter goes), and are charged.  They *will* react with most 
objects
> made of matter - because the nucleus of every atom contains protons.

No - for example positrons have electric charge and therefore will INTERACT
with ALL charged particles irrespective of type. Positrons will only
ANNHILIATE with other electrons however for protons/anti-protons and
neutron/anti-neutrons things are a lot more complicated since they are
each made up of 3 quarks (or anti-quarks) and so and anti-proton can
partially annhilate with a neutron and vice versa.

 ----

What about positrons colliding with Neutrons and producing Protons, (the 
reverse of Beta decay where a Neutron emits an electron and becomes a 
Proton)?

 ----
All
the fundamental conservation laws are satisfied - charge, energy,
momentum. The problem is that conservation of things called \'lepton
number\' and \'baryon number\' are violated. Lepton number, for ordinary
matter, is essentially the number of electron minus the number of
positrons whereas baryon number is the number of protons and neutrons
minus the number of anti-neutrons and anti-protons, again only for normal
matter.

Theorists tell us that at extremely high energies these number
conservation laws are violated - in fact our existence is good proof of
this since we are made of protons, neutrons and electrons so, assuming
the universe started in the Big Bang, something must have generated
particles and not anti-partciles.

Because of this difference between matter and anti-matter it MAY be
possible to build a machine to exploit this and convert particles into
anti-particles but knowing there is such a difference is a long, long way
from exploiting it. In fact the whole process is on very dodgy ground
theoretically, nevermind experimentally, but heck this is science FICTION!
 ----

I postulated the use of such mechanisms by the Ancients to produce 
Antimatter.

 ----
> > X::>5. Aside from the particles having opposite charges, what are the
> >  ::>properties of antimatter?  Does it follow the same rules for 
gravity,
> >  ::>electromagnetism and so on?
>
> Yes.

NO!

For 3 out of 4 of the fundamental forces of nature (strong,
electromagnetic and gravity) they are thought to be (and to within
measurements they are) the same but there IS a difference between matter
and anti-matter for the weak force!
 ----

Which is what "Nuclear Dampers" are supposed to muck about with....

 ----
If you look at the decays of neutral kaons (a types of mesons made from a
strange and a down quark) then you see a difference between matter and
anti-matter. The clearest example of this is that the two decays:

        KL -> Pi+ Mu- Nubar

and     KL -> Pi- Mu+ Nu

(Pi= pion, Mu=muon, Nu=muon neutrino. Pi+/-, Mu+/- and Nu/Nubar are
particle/antiparticle pairs.)

occur with a difference frequency. This means that Pi- are produced more
often than Pi+, for example, and so the weak force (which is responsible
for this decay) sees some difference between them. The exactly mechanism
as to why is not known, although several theories exist. In fact the
experiment I\'m working on at CERN is currently trying to discover the
mechanism behind this effect so hang around a few years and we may find out!
 ----

This was the particle decay I refered to in my response but there exists the 
possibility of more such symmetry breaking stuff at higher energy levels.
I also heard the above decay is handy for describing Left and Right to 
Aliens that don\'t have any other common reference ;)

Django.
