This would make a good plot for a novel, too.  >>Als
Gregor Samsa eines Morgens aus unruhigen Traumen erwachte,
fand er sich in seinem Bett zu ein ungeheueres Psychischer
verwandelt.<<

So Citizen Samsa learns to his shock and horror that he
has great psionic powers.  When?  Maybe as early as the day
in first grade that he gives the school bully a bloody
nose just by wishing it. Maybe the day in his early teens
he pleads with his family to please stop shouting into his
mind at some stressful family holiday gathering.  

The Psionics Institute might hear of this and take an
interest in young Citizen Samsa and provide a shepherd to
guide him through the maze of life in straight society
(always called "deadheads" in my universe by psionics and
Zhodani) with a bent mind.  That won\'t produce a very
honest citizen, so let\'s change the story.

Young Citizen Samsa suppresses his psionics at the strong
encouragement of his terrified parents, but, becoming
alienated from his true nature, develops into a juvenile
delinquent who eventually lashes out....  No, wait, let\'s
tell _your_ story.

Young Citizen Samsa suppresses his psionics once he
becomes aware of them because he\'s able to spot the clues
in society that show what\'s ok behavior and what isn\'t. 
He grows into adulthood, does his education and military
service, gets a decent job, marries per the customs of his
homeworld, etc.  

Everything is ok, except, once in a while, he can\'t help
but hear his spouse\'s thoughts about her ex, or the boss\'s
perverse obsession with another staffer\'s child, and, to
deal with it, he goes a little nuts.  Just a little.  Like
going for a drink after and work and finding himself in a
cab with a professional companion laughing at his nausea
at 4 a.m.  Like spending all weekend so totally
reorganizing his house that no one can find anything
anymore.  Like sitting in his office holding his head in
his hands and feeling such pain and fear that he wishes he
were somewhere else -- anywhere -- and finding himself
skidding to a stop in his old room in his mom\'s house, half
a world away.

(A) Then Citizen Samsa can\'t stand it anymore and he tries
suicide which puts him into the hands of a psychotherapist
(like in The Lathe of Heaven by LeGuin).  The
psychotherapist figures out the problem -- it\'s no doubt
gotten into the textbooks in the 300 years since the
Psionics Suppressions -- and (1) calls the authorities
(see my earlier posting on this subject); (2) calls the
Psionics Institute (only on a 12+, DM +1 if pop B+, etc.);
(3) prescribes a course of therapy to (a) minimize the
psychic disruptions caused by suppression of psionic powers
and (b) empower Citizen Samsa to deal with it and get a
life, or (4) some combination of (1), (2), (3).  

-or-

(B) Then Citizen Samsa can\'t stand it anymore and he tries
suicide, which wakes him up.  He goes to the authorities,
who are dumbfounded at first that the violator of an
offense that hasn\'t been prosecuted in 300 years would turn
himself in, but, like authorities, they think better safe
than sorry:  "\'You can\'t go out, you are arrested.\'  "So it
seems,\' said K.  \'But what for?\' he added.  \'We are not
authorized to tell you that.\'"  Then, maybe, like Joseph
K, Citizen Samsa is "\'under arrest, certainly, but that
need not hinder [him] from going about [his] business\'",
especially if that business is as important to the state as
working at the bank or an insurance company.  

Or maybe they put hiim into a mental institution because
he\'s exhibiting delusional behavior -- thinking he can read
minds and teleport.  Or maybe they torture him until he
signs a release donating himself to a research facility.
Or maybe they prosecute him for "using an enumerated
psionic capability, as defined in Regina Penal Code sec.
15004, to wit, telepathy", and send him to jail for 20
years or until another prisoner kills him because psis are
lower in the prison hierarchy than child molesters.  Or
maybe they send him to the psychotherapist -- see above.
Or maybe they try to get him to emigrate to the Zhodani
Consulate, who are probably the only people who can help
him at this point in his life, but who may not want the
burden.  

Or maybe the case becomes known, and takes on a life of
its own.  The Ine Givar start a campaign of terrorism and
litigation to get him released, and use him in their
propaganda as an example of Imperial oppression.  The
hard-line anti-psionics people (how many of them are there
by the 1100s IE? I would guess as many as hard line
abolitionists around in 1995 CE.  We\'re all abolitionists 
now.  Oh, you\'re a slave owner?  Well, you\'ll have to start 
paying your slaves the minimum wage now.  No, we won\'t send 
you to jail.  We haven\'t done that in -- how long?) want to 
kill him.  The criminal defense bar wants his due process 
rights protected, like any other criminal.  Etc. 

Again, it depends on the world at which he goes to the
authorities.  How does that culture deal with those far
outside certain norms?

This could be a fun one to role-play.  One player playing 
the psionic and the referee playing all the authorities?  
One member of a group of adventurers playing the psionic, 
the others playing his possibly former friends -- "He\'s 
what! a telepath! and we spent how long together in that 
crashed cutter waiting for rescue?  I\'ll never be able to 
take enough showers to feel clean again!"?  The referee 
playing the psionic and the players playing the various 
authorities?

Hmmm.

--Glenn
