    'body' => 'Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> writes:

> 1.  According to many, it is impossible to get more energy out of
> antimatter than one puts into creating it.  I am of course familiar with
> the laws of conservation.  But one can get more energy out of a log than
> one puts into it by burning it.  This is because the log contains energy
> which is released by a chemical reaction.

Nope, you do *not get more energy out of the log than was "put into"
it. The energy input was that required to take water, CO2, and various
minerals and turn them into wood. Believe me, the plant needed a *lot*
more energy to do this than what you get out by burning it.

> I guess my basic question is: 
> why does it take so much energy to change the charge of a particle?

You *can\'t* "change the charge" of a particle. That\'d violate a
conservation law. What you needed to do (before quarks) was "swap" the
charge between some particles, while at the same time shuffling or not
shuffling other conserved properties. But as noted in another article
"baryon number" and "lepton number" conservation made that unworkable.

Now that quarks are known, it gets easier to explain. Everything that
has a baryon number turns out to be made of quarks. Everything with a
lepton number turns out to be made of leptons. And there\'s no way to
turn a lepton into a quark, or vice versa.

So a proton consists of three quarks (I forget which ones) one of each
of the three "colors" (red, green & blue). An antiproton consists of
three quarks as well, but with the opposite "colors". 

> Why
> does one have to put as much energy in as the mass of the whole thing,
> isn\'t it just a matter of taking a mass and changing a property of it? 

It\'s a matter of changing *all* the properties except mass. Charge,
baryon or lepton number, spin, and several others. If one could
"change" the properties that easily, you could just convert matter
directly into energy without bothering with antimatter.

> Or do you have to "build" antimatter from energy?  (forgive my ignorance, I
> let my subscription to "Exotic Particle Monthly" run out a year ago :-)

Bingo! You "split" a sufficiently energetic photon into a particle and
the corresponding antiparticle. Or otherwise supply the energy required
to generate *both particles. Then you try and use eletric and magnetic
fields to capture the antiparticles before they run into something.

The current "best" efficiency in creating antiprotons is at Fermilab,
where it takes approximately sixty million times as much energy to
generate an antiproton as you will get by annihilating it.

> 2. If one stores a bunch of anti-protons in a magnetic bottle, will there 
> be a problem with free neutrons (i.e., radition) getting into the 
> bottle?  Someone said that anti-particles will only react with the same 
> sort of pro-particle, but others contradicted this.  Can I get a bit more 
> input on this issue?  I realize that neutrinoes and such would not be a 
> problem, as they would have low interaction probabilities anyway, and 
> would only "use up" minute amounts of the antimatter anyway, but what 
> about heavier particles?  You could sheild out any charged particles, so 
> I\'m mainly worried about neutral ones.

There aren\'t many free neutrons running around. They are easily kept
out. A neutrino *can\'t* annihilate any part of a proton or anti-proton.
It\'s purely a lepton. And a proton is purely quarks. While they can
interact, you won\'t lose anything that way. The other nuetral particles
are highly unstable and not the sort of thing that you\'ll find laying
around. 

Anti-neutrons *would* be able to react with neutrinos, because they
effectively consist of an anti-proton, a positron, and a neutrino. So
in the rare case where an anti-neutrino wandered by *and* actually
intereacted with the anti-neutron, you\'d wind up with a bit of energy,
and a positron and an anti-proton. 

> 3. If one allows anti-protons to react with normal protons, how much of 
> the energy is released as waste neutrinoes and other "uncatchable" 
> particles?  If I allow the whole mechanism of anti-matter plant to 
> convert 10% of mass to useful energy is that unrealistic?  Fusion\'s .1% 
> conversion, correct?  So this would be 100 times better.

As I noted, the proton and antiproton are made up out of quarks. One
has quarks with red, blue and green charges, the other has ones with
anti-red, anti-blue, and anti-green charges. To understand what
happens, you have to realize that mesons are made of out of *two*
quarks, with opposite "charges (ie and anti-red and a red). 

So it\'s a lot easier to turn into mesons than to turn completely into
energy. A proton/antiproton pair will produce a bunch of mesons of the
variety called pions. On average, you\'ll get three charged pions and
two neutral pions. The neutral pions almost immediately breakdown into
gamma rays. That\'s 40% of the energy. The other 60% is in the charged
pions, which are moving at around 94% of c! So even though they are
shortlived, their life gets "stretched". They\'ll travel about 21 meters
before decaying into muons, you can extract much of the kinetic energy
from them in that distance.

The muons will travel 1.85 km before decaying into electrons and
positrons. So an antimatter rocket needs a *big* nozzle. 

There\'s good explanation of all this in "Indistinguishable from Magic"
by Robert L. Forward. ISBN 0-671-87686-4 $5.99. 

> Okay, the antimatter thing seemed to interest people, so here\'s another 
> one for the physics types:  what the hell are mesons?  A while ago, 
> someone claimed that meson guns were "magic" in the sense that the mesons 
> do not actually go through matter.  Why not?  How massive are they 
> compared to say a neutron?  If you moved them up close to C, couldn\'t 
> they penetrate quite a bit of matter?  How much energy does a meson 
> release upon decay (or is this another bit of "magic")?  Wouldn\'t you 
> have to get huge numbers of them into the enemy ship to do significant 
> damage?

Mesons, as noted are quark *pairs*, rather than triplets. They are a
few hundred times as massive as an electron. A proton is 1800 times as
massive as an electron.

And yes, they have a limited lifetime. But it is a "half-life" That
means that on average *half* of them will decay *by* that time. A
quarter of them will last twice as long. And eight will last three
times as long, etc. So there\'ll be this long *trail* of decaying mesons
leading from the meson gun to the ship, and past it.

Also, they aren\'t likely to just pass harmlessly through matter.
They\'ll *smash* their way through. 

> From: Roger Moore <moore@hep.phy.cam.ac.uk>

> No - for example positrons have electric charge and therefore will INTERACT

> with ALL charged particles irrespective of type. Positrons will only 
> ANNHILIATE with other electrons however for protons/anti-protons and 
> neutron/anti-neutrons things are a lot more complicated since they are 
> each made up of 3 quarks (or anti-quarks) and so and anti-proton can 
> partially annhilate with a neutron and vice versa.

And an anti-neutron can partially annihilate with an electron.

> Yes it is! Electromagnetic containment works but is limited to extremely 
> small amounts of anti-matter and it also has a limited life time since it\'s

> not possible to create a perfect vacuum so some will interact with air.

According to Dr. Forward, they\'ve used a Penning trap to hold one
hundred thousand antiprotons for *two months* without losing any. 

That\'s not a huge amount, but they figure they can get as many as a
trillion anti-protons into one. That\'s about 300 joules of energy. And
the trap uses a 9-volt battery for power. Of course, the liquid helium
dewar (oversized thermos :-) is a little bulky. 

So it *does* look like it\'s merely a matter of engineering to be able
to store even more.

> Yes we do BUT only for small quantities for small amounts of time.

Two months isn\'t "small". And since they are finding medical uses for
antiprotons, there *will* be continuing work on getting the cost down,
and the storage times up.

