    'from' => 'Robert Flammang FLAMMANG@vms.cis.pitt.ed',
    'body' => 'Hi.

There has been a lot said about antimatter on the list lately, most of
it quite good. There have been a few misconceptions stated here tho,
that I\'d like to correct before the subject peters out.

Misconception #1 -- An anti-particle has the "opposite spin" of its
particle. This is not true at all, an anti-particle has the same spin as
its coresponding particle. The authors of this statement may have meant
to say that the anti-particle\'s magnetic moment is equal to the negative
of its particle\'s magnetic moment, which is true. Or they may have been
thinking of helicity; a MASSLESS particle with definite helicity (like
the neutrino) will have an anti-particle with opposite helicity. Massive
particles never have a lorentz-invariant helicity, so this rule does not
apply to them.

Misconception #2:

>out. A neutrino *can\'t* annihilate any part of a proton or anti-proton.
>It\'s purely a lepton. And a proton is purely quarks. While they can
>interact, you won\'t lose anything that way. The other nuetral particles
>are highly unstable and not the sort of thing that you\'ll find laying
>around. 

A neutrino could react with an anti-proton to make an electron and an
anti-neutron. You would not be able to hold the anti-neutron in a
magnetic bottle. This wouldn\'t happen too often tho.

>Anti-neutrons *would* be able to react with neutrinos, because they
>effectively consist of an anti-proton, a positron, and a neutrino. So
>in the rare case where an anti-neutrino wandered by *and* actually
>intereacted with the anti-neutron, you\'d wind up with a bit of energy,
>and a positron and an anti-proton. 

I\'m not sure what you mean by "effectively consist", but I\'m sure that
the positron (ie, anti-electron) content of the neutron is pretty darn
small. That\'s ok though, since quarks and leptons do interact with one
another by way of the nuclear weak force, and also (for electrons, muons
and taus) by way of the electromagnetic force. So your anti-neutrino
would come in, react with one of the anti-down quarks in the
anti-neutron, turn it into an anti-up quark, and turn itself into a
positron. Meanwhile the anti-neutron (two anti-down quarks and one
anti-up quark) has been turned into an anti-proton (one anti-down quark
and two anti-up quarks.)

>> From: Roger Moore <moore@hep.phy.cam.ac.uk>
>> ... for example positrons have electric charge and therefore will INTERACT 
>> with ALL charged particles irrespective of type. Positrons will only 
>> ANNHILIATE with other electrons however for protons/anti-protons and 
>> neutron/anti-neutrons things are a lot more complicated since they are 
>> each made up of 3 quarks (or anti-quarks) and so and anti-proton can 
>> partially annhilate with a neutron and vice versa.

Yes!

>And an anti-neutron can partially annihilate with an electron.

NO! See above. Weak interactions can (and will, after 11 minutes or so)
cause an anti-neutron to decay into a an anti-proton, but it does not
anhilate or partially anhilate.

	=	=	=	=	=	=	=	=

Now to move onto another topic...

>I suspect that the architect of "Meson Guns" in Traveller was either unaware
>of the nature of the particles, or had managed to get mesons and neutrinos
>confused, or just ignored the whole thing for a nifty-sounding weapon. :-)
>
>wildstar@qrc.com

I think the idea came from meson gun experiments in Geneva, where
medical researchers fired charged meson beams into the brain tumors of
patients. The pions burned the tumor area, while leaving the intervening
brain matter RELATIVELY unscathed.

The science behind this comes from a peak at the end of the meson\'s
Bragg spectrum. A Bragg spectrum is a plot of the amount of ionizing
energy deposited per cm (dE/dX) by a charged particle travelling thru
matter. The Bragg Peak indicates that a charged particle deposits more
energy per cm towards the end of its path, as it\'s running out of kinetic
energy (ie, braking to a stop in the target material).

In addition to making this peak of ionizing energy, a meson will decay
rather quickly once it stops and it\'s lifetime is no longer
relativisticly dilated. If it\'s a heavy positive meson, it\'s decay
products often contain, among other thinks, a very energetic positron.
The energetic positron quickly strikes one of the nearby electrons and
makes a pair of high-energy gamma rays.

It was these gamma rays that ultimately nixed the pion as a medical
tool. (Everyone uses protons, which are stable and do not decay, these
days.) But as a weapon, the positive meson would be the "exploding bullet"
of subatomic particles. Their Bragg curve makes them ideal for
penetrating external armor, then doing ionizing damage when they stop.
(You tune the energy so they stop inside the ship. You need to estimate
the Hull thickness to do this.) When, they stop, they make, ultimately,
lots of gamma rays and neutrinos, thereby cooking a heavily armored ship
from the inside.

They are less than ideal for hitting a thin, unarmored target, since you
would have to tune them very accurately to do this.

As I said, I THINK this is the inspiration for the Traveller guns. But
real-life meson guns are not magic. To say they "pass thru intervening
matter without interacting" is a gross exageration. Say rather, "they
pass through intervening matter without interacting quite so much."


				-Rob



