    'topic' => 'Psionics',
    'body' => 'Hi there

I think that Psionics *is/was* illegal in the Imperium (at least the 
Imperial Encylopedia library data refers to it as the "...criminal use of 
mental powers...").  However, like murder, member states were able to 
decide the fate of those caught in breach according to local law; the 
Imperial Law just provided the minimum standard for the entire territory 
of the empire.  What the Imperium\'s reaction to a psionic would be 
probably depends on the noble or military commander/civil administrator 
called upon to judge the case.  As the Imperial nobility had a wide range 
of views (as wide as the worlds of the Imperium) punishments would 
probably range as widely as they would from any other source.  Of course, 
it is always possible that Imperial nobles would have pro-psi sympathies, 
and so act to protect the psionic (while still appearing to uphold the 
law).  Another alternative is that an unscrupulous noble (Lucan being the 
big daddy of these) might force the psionic into working for them in 
return for their continued existence.  In any system that supresses some 
naturally iccuring aspect of a person\'s make-up, there will always be 
those who use that supression to their own ends.

In general, you might treat the anti-psi predudice in a similar manner to 
the anti-gay attitude; many (perhaps the majority) abhor the psionic without 
any understanding what it actually means to be psionic, some have a 
fascination with psionics (in a perverse fation which grows from 
mis-understanding) and many just don\'t consider it at all, as it never 
enters into their lives.  There may even be a section of society in which 
being psionic is more acceptable (as with the acting profession and 
gays).  In general, the attitude to gay people at the turn of the century 
in England may be a good guide.  A psionic equivalent of Oscar Wilde?

Stewart
