    'body' => 'I am working on the real history of the Civil War of 604-622, and have
prepared the working hypothesis set forth below.  My objectives are (1) to
insert the people of the Imperium into this part of its history and (2) to
begin to explain the structure of the Imperial Navy ca. 1100.  I solicit
your responses.

The antebellum Imperial Navy emphasized ties of personal fealty to nobles
commanding ships and fleets, in a manner analogous to the land-based
Imperial feudal system.  Thus admiral of a large fleet might be like a duke,
and the squadrons would be led by commodores who were essentially his
vassals.  The ships\' captains, in turn, who owed personal loyalty to their
commodores, and the crews came from the same planets and owed loyalty to the
captain.  All oaths of fealty ultimately led to, and included, the Emperor,
of course, but ship crews were connected by blood and birthplace, and flag
officers were connected by the noble system or an analogue of it.

The Civil War erupted when Grand Admiral of the Marches Olav hault-Plankwell
won the First Frontier War and found enough discontent among Imperial
subjects, and the Navy, and the bureaucracy in the Imperium\'s handling of it
to indicate that an attempt on the throne would be supported.  What he did
not count on was other admirals finding the same thing and taking advantage
of it.  Hault-Plankwell got to Capital first, but other admirals were on the
way with their fleets.

The war lasted eighteen years, characterized by "fringe battles for power
bases, and central battles for power in the Core."  (Imperial Encyclopedia,
p. 21)  During the war, fleet supply became the critical issue.  No admiral
could attack Capital unless the fleet was in repair and had fuel, missiles
and other ammunition, and food.  Initially, the worlds from which the ships
and crews were drawn supplied them willinglly, but as the war dragged on,
the worlds began to suffer greater hardships in providing war materiel.

In addition, the "fringe battles" were fought for and too often on the most
productive worlds.  Sabotage of shipyards and weapons factories that could
not be turned to one faction\'s use gave way to terrorist attacks and raids
from space.  Shipyards and weapons factories were later supplanted as
primary targets by food processing factories, then cultivated land, then
atmospheres and hydrospheres.

The fleets thus found themselves at war not just with one another but with
the worlds of the Imperium.  In some regions, the fleets were little more
than unusually well-armed pirates, able to conquer whole worlds, but not to
hold them for long against other, similar fleets.  The rounds of conquest
and reconquest took their toll, and the worlds\' productivity dropped.

Each world of the Imperium, while largely defenseless alone, knew or assumed
that other worlds were faced with the same problems.  Agents began to travel
among the worlds, circulating variations of the same treason:  resist the
Navy.  Arbellatra, who had stayed out of the fighting as much as possible,
while defending the Spinward Marches from Vargr, Sword Worlds, and Aslan
opportunists (and Zhodani covert actions), had developed an effective
intelligence department.  Her intelligence staff learned of the new action
by the various worlds, and reported to her.

Instead of a new difficulty, Arbellatra saw opportunity, and started sending
her own agents into the regions of the other admirals, to sow similar
dissension in their worlds.  Her agents had an additional message, however,
which was that the Spinward Marches were better off than elsewhere, because
Arbellatra did not have to crush the worlds with in-kind taxes and forced
labor, because she did not waste her fleets on trying to usurp the throne.
Arbellatra was really the only patriotic admiral, just following her orders
to defend her assigned portion of the realm from all enemies -- foreign and
domestic.

With the advent of the Second Frontier War in 615, Arbellatra began to
increase the size of her fleet in three ways:  with increased shipbuilding
in the Spinward Marches, with donations from nearby admirals, who were glad
to have a neutral force at their backs while they fought each other, and, to
a lesser extent, from captured Outworld Coalition ships.  By the end of the
war in 620, Arbellatra was in Plankwell\'s enviable position:  leader of a
victorious, consolidated fleet, and the winner of a war grossly mismanaged
by the rest of the Imperial defense establishment.  In addition, she had
capably managed public opinion, that had come to detest the admirals as much
as any gang of pirates, to distinguish her as an admiral who was not trying
to be a usurper and who could be trusted not to crush the worlds under her
charge.

Arbellatra took power, but declared that she held it only "in trust for a
rightful successor" to Jacqueline.  (IE, at 21)  She put down the remaining
admirals by gaining the support of the Moot and the worlds.  The worlds
began to resist the roving fleets in earnest, and to declare for the Regent
Arbellatra.  The nobility supported her efforts to starve the remaining
fleets.  The fleets were by now so exhausted -- and often mutinous -- that
the Civil War ended in within two years.

Among Arbellatra\'s post-war programs were reform of the Navy and, after she
became Empress, reinvestment of power with the landed nobility.  The Navy\'s
practices of oaths of personal loyalty and same-world ship crews and
squadrons were replaced with a generic oath to serve the Emperor and the
Imperium, and systems of personnel rotation.  Naval personnel -- officers
and other ranks -- were (and are still by 1100) intentionally sent during
their careers into different regions of the Imperium, normally serving only
a few years on any single ship.  This policy entailed movement of naval
families and some enlargement of naval bases to accomodate them.

Thank you for your attention.  Your comments and criticism are appreciated.

--Glenn

