    'topic' => ' Civil War (XBd#463)',
    'body' => 'FIRST IMPERIAL CIVIL WAR THREAD
 ===============================
   My take on the First Civil war is that it was similar to the wars of the
Age of Enlightenment. The Navies fought each other, requisitioned what they
needed from worlds, and otherwise left civilians alone. (Well, I also figure
merchant spacemen were subject to impressment, but the navies still left the
ships and merchant lines running.)
   It was not a war of populations--in most cases! Some power blocs/factions
probably had a cultural bent to them. The Imperial policy of absorbing
worlds and pocket empires probably left a lot of little factions around.
This might have been the most colorful of the Imperium\'s wars.
   Overall, though, the nobility was not directly involved. The Archdukes
are not mentioned. The lesser nobility, while also unmentioned, probably
contributed sons to the navies. This severely limits any theory of cultural
splits being behind the blocs.

SIZE Of NAVY
 ============
   The Imperium had been growing, just reaching Terra shortly before the
war. Consequently, as worlds were still recovering from the Long Night, I
assumed poulations were much smaller than they were in 1116. With the tech
level of the times, I _estimated_ the Navy only had one-eighth as many ships
as it did in 1116.
   The largest capital ships could have been up to one-million tons, but the
design philosophy was still for one ship meets all functions. (Like the
Tigress in Naval Ships.)
   Nothing is said about its organization. Squadrons and fleets based around
high-pop worlds could have continued cultural splits--but, again, nothing is
said. So I didn\'t add that to my compilation.

PERSONALITIES
 =============
   I thought about what a Shakespeare might do with the Civil War. There
wasn\'t space in the article to use it, so I didn\'t develop the musings.
   Plankwell comes off as a MacBeth. Oh, such bloody hands.
   Cleon V would probably be a towering, tragic figure like Caesar. That
Arbellatra\'s authority originated with him would only contribute to a
Shakespeare making him a white knight.
   Donald would best fit as King Lear. Successful, but family troubles.
(What was Emdiri to him?)
   Would Arbellatra be Henry V or Jeanne d\'Arc?
   What to make of Gustus, the last _man_ standing? :-)  His fall seems to
have been delayed by maneuver, but inevitable. Was he cleaning up the mess,
a Johny-come-lately, or what? And being Emperor he can\'t cut a deal with
Arbellatra. I suspect his cause was marked by growing desperation and
defections.

   The rest seem rather faceless in the history. They had to have their own
stories, though.
   I went so far as to determine that Catherine (less than three months in
619) came from Gateway. She was avenging Donald; her murderer, Ramon II, was
avenging Emdiri. Catherine\'s squadrons got away from Ramon with Catherine\'s
heir and settled an unpopulated world in Verge. The tie to Catherine was a
noble family\'s dark secret...but the adventure didn\'t run at the con, and
the Rebellion soon made such a secret fairly insignificant.
