[Trying this again....]

Clay wrote:

>   Overall, though, the nobility was not directly involved. The Archdukes
>are not mentioned. The lesser nobility, while also unmentioned, probably
>contributed sons to the navies. This severely limits any theory of cultural
>splits being behind the blocs.

Well, the nobility was involved to some degree in the machinations of the
confirmation process in the Moot, as moot as confirmation was during the
Civil War.  We know the Moot was very divided about who should be emperor
starting as early as Jerome, and this didn\'t help end the Civil War.  It
was "radical nobles in the Moot" that backed the uprising that killed
Cleon V, for instance -- maybe not with worlds or fleets so much as with
their political support.  In my opinion, at least some of these "radical
nobles" were probably hard-line members of the Solomani Movement, which
may explain some of the division in the Moot.  If nobles supporting the
Solomani Movement controlled a large part of the Civil War moot, it might
help explain why all the barracks emperors were pure Solomani -- it was
required to have a chance at confirmation.

Also, recall that we know the Archduke of Antares was forcibly replaced
by Empress Arbellatra for not supporting her, and from what we know of
him, he would have gotten along well with the Solomani hard-line.

>   I thought about what a Shakespeare might do with the Civil War. There
>wasn\'t space in the article to use it, so I didn\'t develop the musings.

I\'ve thought similar things about the Second Civil War.  The stories of
the bloody reformer Dulinor and fratricidal Lucan, the chaotic end of
Brzk and heroic stand of Norris (written by a Denebian playwright, of
course, for appropriate Shakespearian bias) could make some nice history
plays....

>   Would Arbellatra be Henry V or Jeanne d\'Arc?

If Arbellatra is Henry V, does that cast the Solomani Sphere as France?  :)

>   What to make of Gustus, the last _man_ standing? :-)  His fall seems to
>have been delayed by maneuver, but inevitable. Was he cleaning up the mess,
>a Johny-come-lately, or what? And being Emperor he can\'t cut a deal with
>Arbellatra. I suspect his cause was marked by growing desperation and
>defections.

Not to mention that he murdered Martin VI to get the Iridium Throne, which
probably required him to have been on Martin\'s staff to get close enough at
that point.  Desperation is about right, too -- after 618, the Moot was
ready to confirm *anybody*.  After going through four emperors in 618,
and another five in 619, things must have looked grim.

>   The rest seem rather faceless in the history. They had to have their own
>stories, though.

Nicolai seems interesting -- he ruled nearly as long as Olav or Cleon V,
scattered the remnants of Olav/Ramon\'s fleet, and managed to win acceptance
by the Moot.  George finally murdered him, and the Moot didn\'t confirm
another emperor until Cleon V.  I can see Joseph supported by the radical
Solomani nobles, which would explain why some nobles would refuse to swear
allegiance to him despite confirmation, putting themselves in a sticky spot.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonnevil@itlabs.umn.edu>

