    'body' => 'EMPEROR NICOLAI
   Nicolai benefitted from coming right after the Plankwell/Ramon war fleet
shot itself up in the Plankwell-Ramon fight. He may have been fairly equal
in strength with other contenders, but nearer Core/Capital. Then it took
time for his competitors to gather enough strength to come after him.
   But still, as a recognized emperor _at that point_ he had a good chance
of pulling the Imperium back together again. That he didn\'t indicated the
other contenders put their own interests before that of the Imperium.
   Maybe he is more like King Lear than the others. A good man at the mercy
of disloyal forces.

RADICALS IN MOOT
   Regarding the "radical nobles": those are just the kinds of things I
wanted to suggest when I invented them and put them into the chronology.
Something like "the mountain" in the French Revolution, they forced people
to make choices by pressing for "radical" change.
   Their presence provided a mechanism by which the fighting would be
continued beyond the point when the reasonable majority would have cried
"enough!"
