    'id' => '<055113141295*/G=Michael/S=Barry/O=FINANCE/PRMD=AUSGOVFINANCE/ADMD=T',
    'topic' => ' Civil War 604-622',
    'body' => 'Glenn

Very nice for a first attempt at a history of the Civil War. This is a good
look at a part of Imperial history that is just crying out for somebody to
write a scenario or a sourcebook, but I doubt if anybody can pry
GDW/Challenge away from their ridiculous Reformation Coalition. Anyway, some
suggestions: - these may have been covered by others already but I\'m not
about to edit every time somebody else has the same good ideas as me.  ;]

1.  I think your objective of explaining the structure of the Navy is coming
along nicely. I like the touch of having Civil War era fleets as feudal
fiefdoms - you are correct in assuming this to be a dangerously unstable
setup. One aspect of this that you have not explored is the high probability
that these feudal fleets within the Imperium had probably been fighting
against each other (on and off) since long before the Civil War; their
objective being to take out rival nobles, seize juicy territory etc rather
than become Emperor. In this situation, the Emperor might just keep out of
their way through fear - have a look at the relationship between the King of
England and the Earl of Warwick when the Earl was known as Kingmaker...
(?maybe around 1500-1600?)

2.  Your explanation of the politics of the Imperium during the Civil War
seems a bit too democratic. Imperial citizens\' opinions wouldn\'t really
matter to the Emperor, the Admirals, the Nobility, or anyone else including
the subjects themselves. Even in the Imperium around 1100 the ordinary
citizen (and most lower-order nobles!) have very little political power. The
power blocs would have been made up of large land-holding nobles (including
the Emperor), feudal fleet admirals, and megacorps.

3.  I got the impression that the Civil War didn\'t destroy the Imperium
because the bureaucracy kept going regardless of who was in charge. I can\'t
see them giving support to any of the factions - they probably functioned
like a feudal fiefdom in themselves, under their own highly hierarchical,
obsessively impartial, magnificently bureaucratic system,  - impenetrable to
your ordinary inbred noble.

4.  From what I know of history, I find it a bit bizarre that a Civil War
could cause minimal damage to the population and political structures.
Historically, civil wars have been a fight to the death mobilising the whole
population into massive repetitive assaults until the winner is the last
pathetic remnant left standing...but I guess if the CT canon says the Civil
War didn\'t do much damage, we work with that.

5.  What happened to the Imperium\'s borders while the fleet admirals were
off eating each others\' tails around Capital? During the civil wars of the
late Roman Empire, rebel generals usually recruited the same barbarians that
the Empire had spent hundreds of years trying to keep out. Once they got a
taste of Roman loot, and once their master had paid them off with very
generous grants of land within the Empire, they stayed around and
contributed nicely to further instability. SOMEBODY had to be maintaining
the borders against the Vargr, Solomani, Aslan, etc other than Arbellatra. I
can\'t imagine the nasties being particularly impressed by the news that
Arbellatra\'s navy away off in the Spinward Marches would come along and
spank their botties if they invaded...

6.  The feudal fleets probably operated on a system of "gentlemans\' war"; a
code of conduct that severely limited what they were allowed to do. eg: all
engagements between fleets only (no bombing planets, no ground warfare, -
therefore little impact on the civilian population), set-piece battles on
agreed battlefields, repatriation of prisoners of war, limited weaponry and
all that chivalrous stuff that hereditary nobles with severely limited gene
pool seemed to find honourable. There is certainly plenty of precedent for
this in history, and it would certainly explain why Arbellatra, just having
won a real, \'dirty\' war, could sweep through this pack of pansies in short
order. Think of Shaka taking over the Zulu tribes...ritual warfare with
feather boas wasn\'t much of a match for the disciplined and experienced Impi
armed with assegai.

