    'index' => 'ac219',
    'topic' => 'Jump Limits',
    'body' => 'Hi there

This is a bit delayed, I\'m afraid, as I\'ve just submitted my thesis!

I looked at the jump diamter problem when I discovered that for
planets orbitting large stars (giants/supergiants), then the only way
to make them a comfortable temperature was to place them so far within
the jump limit that it took 1 week+ to reach them.  This didn\'t fit in
with the worlds I was creating; they usually weren\'t wonderful garden
worlds, so the chances are they would be passed by, as they also were
not in strategic locations.

I solved this problem ny linking the jump diameter limit to the mass
of the body near which you are jumping.  For planetary bodies, with
earth-like densities, the 100 diameter rule is pretty close.  Stars
and gas giants have a much lower density, resulting in a lower jump
distance.  In the end, I said that the important thing was the *rate
of change* of gravity with distance that mattered.  Thus, you could
jump safely when the change in gravity over the length of your ship,
or over the short distance it moves during jump insertion, is
sufficiently small.  I now work out jump distance using one of two
formulae, depending on the central object:

J-dist=117.5*(cube root of star\'s mass from tables) million km for stars

J-dist=1.28*(cube root of planet\'s mass) million km for planets and gas giants
      =160*(cube root of density)*(UWP size) thousand km

All the masses and densities, etc. can be determined with Grand
Survey/World Builder\'s Handbook/whatever that T:TNE thing is called.
This gives answers for planets similar to those with the basic rules,
but also make stellar jump diamters more sensible.  I think in the
case of some big stars, it is possible to come out *inside* it, if you
are not careful about your destination coordinates.

