    'body' => '

Dear Stewart,

You wrote:

 > Hi there

Hello.


 > Was  it you  who asked  all the  questions re.  Starshi Combat on
 > XTML?

Yep, it was me.


 > If so,  what were the results?  I\'d be interested in  any rule
 > ideas you have.

I was  interested   not  in  the   rules  per  se,   but  in  the
ramifications of  the rules, and  their effect upon  strategy and
tactics in intership and space-based combat.

Here\'s what I learned:

Sensor  and weapon  range determine  the type  of space conflicts
which can occur.

    In  a  campaign  with   long-range  sensors  (and  long-range
    weapons), because  sensors (and weapons)  are limited to  the
    speed of  light, the delay in  time between the image  of the
    target travelling  from the target to  the firing vessel, and
    the delay  in time for  the weapon fire  to reach the  target
    vessel, scoring a hit is highly unlikely if the target vessel
    is evading (altering course often).

    Thus, a single  weapon (such as a spinal  mount) could easily
    be   dodged,  and   it   would   take  many   weapons  firing
    simultaneously in guessing patterns to make a hit likely.

    The  shorter  the  range  to  the  target, the less effective
    evasion becomes.


    Long-range  weapons would  allow  spacecraft  to jump  into a
    system, lock on to  planetary targets (adjusting for movement
    variables such as speed of orbit and rotation), fire upon the
    target, and leave the system before defensive action could be
    taken.  There is  little  defense  against an  energy weapon,
    because you can\'t see it before it hits you.

    To  prevent or  reduce the  effects of  the same  tactic from
    working  on  peaceful  ships,  those  ships  would need to be
    engaged  in  evasive  maneuvers  (randomized  by computer) as
    standard  operating procedure  at all  times. Otherwise, they
    could be picked off like  flies by long-range fire which they
    wouldn\'t know was coming until it hit them.

    The shorter the range of  weapons, the less effective hit and
    run becomes.


    In  a  campaign  with   short-range  sensors  and  long-range
    weapons, the hit-and-run tactic against large visible targets
    (planets) is  strengthened, as the  attacker remains for  all
    intents and purposes invisible.

    Ship-to-ship combat is deadlier in such campaigns, because in
    order to see the enemy, they  have to be fairly close to you,
    reducing the effectiveness of evasion. Though ship encounters
    would  be much  less common.

    Search and destroy missions  in space resemble groping around
    in the dark. Ships in  interplanetary space become needles in
    a haystack.

    Protecting against and catching  smuggling and pirate vessels
    is  harder.  The  shorter  the  range  of  sensors,  the less
    effective  sweeps (patrols)  become.

    For ship-to-ship combat purposes,  it provides little benefit
    to have energy weapons of greater range than your sensors.

    The longer the range of sensors,  the easier it is to protect
    a system against piracy.  Refueling points become much easier
    to secure.


    In  a  campaign  with  short-range  sensors  and  short-range
    weapons,  ship-to-ship combat  is about  the same  as in  the
    example above.

    But  the  hit-and-run  tactic  is  reduced  in effectiveness,
    because the attacking ship must  get too close to the planet,
    increasing the likelihood of running  into a patrol, or being
    spotted  by  the  planet   (which  likely  has  longer  range
    sensors). By the time you move into position, the planet will
    have spotted you.


    Things  really start  to get  interesting when  you vary  the
    range of  sensors and weapons based  on ship (and powerplant)
    size.


Digest Group Publications did a  lot of work on the MegaTraveller
rules. Of everything in the  main rulebooks, the sensors and ship
weapons  section  of  the  vehicle  construction  chapter  in the
referee\'s manual left the most to be desired.

We just want to do a better job with our upcoming sci-fi release.

Hopefully, the above observations will give us a basis upon which
to adjust the ranges made available  in the setting (to the limit
of technological level, of course).

Thanks for your interest.

Sincerely,

Roger Sanger
Digest Group Publications

