    'from' => 'Phillip McGregor aspqrz@sydney.DIALix.oz',
    'topic' => 'Traveller Technology',
    'body' => 'Hi!

Just read the queries about the backward nature of Traveller technology, and
I thought I\'d add my 2c worth --

The clues are all there in the pre-Virus material - and it boils down to this,
the Terrans (and the Darrians, which were Terran influenced *without* Vilani
contact) were able to make massive advances in the Interstellar Wars that led
to the collapse of the Nasu Sirka, and trashed the Vilani, who were not. The
difference was that Terran *society* was one where individualism and the idea
of progress were *not* the dirty words that they were in the Vilani Empire.
The Terrans would, quite probably, have completely transformed Vilani society
in the aftermath of the collapse, except for the treason of the Fleet, led
by Admiral Estigaribbia ... as they planned to subsume the Vilani Empire into
the Terran mainstream. While this would have been unpleasant in the short term
for the Vilani, it would have been much better in the long term - as the
increased technology that would have resulted from untrammlled Terran techno
research would have been much more than they could have expected themselves.

Unfortunately, Estigarribbia and the Fleet were obviously a minority (despite
their justifications that they "understood the plight of the conquered" -
obvious propaganda of no value) amongst the whole set-up, and *required* the
support of the Vilani bureaucrats to set themselves up. The "price" for such a
deal - up front *and* as part of the ongoing Vilani influence (domination would
not be too fine a point to put on it!) in the bureacracy - adoption of a whole
variety of Vilani social attitudes ... including the strictures against "too
quick" technological research.

It is likely, though difficult to tell for certain, that the Traitors had to
use Vilani bureaucrats and security personnel to help their occupation of the
Terran Federation, as they were (as already noted) in a tiny minority. Terran
society was thus placed under the control of the ultra-conservative Vilani, and
their iron hand crushed Terran inventiveness and progressive ideas. Sure, the
society was not completely vilanified, but it *was* modified enough that it
lost the "edge" that it had had.

There\'s a lot more, of course, and I have (modestly) put together a complete
alternative history for the Imperium and Terra from before the Interstellar
wars through to 1120 - one which completely deletes Virus and provides an
explanation for the whole backward mess that the Imperium is (and will, likely,
*always* be until somebody reforms its society - by crushing it).

A small number of extra copies are available at a modest cost, as are a number
of other supplements that provide advanced tech for Starship Design (based on
High Guard), Personal Equipment, Planetary Vehicles and, as I get around to it,
Starships and Military Weapons. If you\'re interested, drop me a line and I\'ll
answer questions and provide further details ... but, one up front, none of the
stuff is FF&S compatible, as the so-called "advanced" technology provided
there, though it certainly fits in with the backward Imperium, has no claim to
be "advanced" at all!

Phil (Space Opera/Rigger Black Book) McGregor

